<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DemocraticChairs Bjt   11-19 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democratic Chairs, Bjt,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Party Leaders Urge Kirk To Stay As National Chairman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The post-election meeting of Democratic state
party leaders is turning into a Paul Kirk tribute.
   Throughout the opening session Friday of a two-day meeting of the
Association of State Democratic Chairs, party leaders appealed to
Kirk to serve another four years as national party chairman.
   ``We need you,'' former Arizona governor Bruce Babbitt told Kirk
at a luncheon in his honor.
   Babbitt turned to Kirk's wife, Gail, and said, ``You have only
one husband to give to your party and, damn it, we need him for
another four years.''
   When Kirk rose to address the association at a post luncheon
meeting, the state party leaders chanted, ``Four more years, four
more years.''
   ``We must urge him and, if need be, draft him for another term,''
said Sam Shipley, the Delaware Democratic Party chairman.
   But Kirk gave the party officials no encouragement, except to say
he would not make a decision until after Thanksgiving.
   ``Four years is a long time,'' he said. ``Eight years is twice as
long.''
   Waiting in the wings should Kirk step down in February when his
four-year term ends were five contenders for the post _ four of whom
said they would not run if Kirk agrees to serve a second term.
   The one exception was Ron Brown, a Washington lawyer and former
party official, who was convention manager for Jesse Jackson.
   ``Obviously, it changes the equation tremendously,'' he said when
asked what he would do if Kirk agreed to seek another term.
   Many party officials have said they oppose Brown because of his
tie to Jackson.
   ``Jesse's a friend,'' said Brown. ``I'm proud of the role I
played in the Jackson campaign ... but I'm my own person, not his
person.''
   The other potential contenders for the party leadership post were
Rick Wiener, chairman of the Michigan Democratic Party and president
of the state chairs association, and former congressmen Michael
Barnes of Maryland, James Jones of Oklahoma and Jim Stanton of Ohio.
   Kirk urged the Democrats to avoid divisive battles, ``region
against region, left against right, constituency against
constituency.''
   He cited Democratic gains in 1988 elections for state and local
offices and said, ``There is no Republican mandate.''
   The Democrats have lost five of the last six presidential
elections, but Kirk urged the party not to ``fall into the trap of
thinking we must change everything we've done in order to win the
next presidential election.''
   There was sentiment at the meeting for re-examining, once again,
the party rules for selecting presidential nominees.
   ``We need to visit that process,'' said John Baker, Alabama party
chairman, who added he wasn't certain what, if any, changes ought to
be made.
   Barnes suggested he thought changes made at the 1988 convention
as part of a compromise with Jackson might be rescinded.
   One of those changes reduced the future influence of party and
elected officials at conventions.
   ``We want to get elected officials, people with constituencies,
up front in the nominating process,'' said the former congressman.
</TEXT>
