<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FAA-Controllers     11-19 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FAA-Controllers,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transport Chief Orders Review Of Air Safety In Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has been
ordered to conduct an immediate review of the busy Northeast
corridor air traffic control system because of a series of errors
that involved Air Force One, according to an unpublished letter.
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley ordered the review in a
letter to FAA Administrator Allan McArtor earlier this week, two
days after a federal investigation revealed that a string of
controller errors caused Air Force One and a commuter plane to fly
too close to one another over New Jersey last month.
   A copy of the letter was obtained Friday by The Associated Press.
   The two aircraft came within 500 feet vertically and 1.5 miles
horizontally as they both began a descent into Newark International
Airport on Oct. 12, about half as close as is normally allowed by
federal regulation.
   The National Transportation Safety Board earlier this week urged
a review of the air traffic control operations in the Northeast
after concluding its investigation into the incident.
   The safety board said while the president's plane never may have
been in danger of a collision, the incident revealed problems that
could lead to ``an erosion of safety in (the) high density Northeast
(air traffic) system.''
   At times during the Oct. 12 incident, some air controllers
handling traffic near Air Force One did not know the location of the
president's jet as it flew from Philadelphia to Newark, and in one
case two controllers noticed the president's jet and the Bar Harbor
Airlines commuter plane converging but did not raise an alarm.
   Burnley in his Nov. 17 letter to McArtor said the NTSB
investigation ``describes a series of managerial, operational and
training deficiencies that, I am sure you agree, are unacceptable.''
   Burnley directed McArtor to proceed immediately with a broad
``system safety and efficiency'' review of air traffic control
procedures at the four FAA facilties near Washington, New York and
Philadelphia similar to one conducted after a string of controller
errors at Chicago's O'Hare International Airport.
   Burnley also said he wanted the responsiblity for controller
quality assurance separated from the air traffic control bureacracy
and brought directly under the FAA administrator by Dec. 7.
   ``This (current) organizational structure simply has not
worked,'' Burnley said in the letter. He noted that the NTSB report
had cited controller problems that had been acknowledged as early as
l986 and ``remained uncorrected a year or two later'' at both the
Washington and New York air traffic control centers.
   He said eight of 14 operational problems found in a l987 review
of air traffic procedures at the Washington center ``remained
uncorrected over a year later.''

</TEXT>
