<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Dubcek,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Czechoslovak Leader Meets Italian Socialists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek, the former Czechoslovak Communist
Party leader ousted in 1968 after a Soviet-led invasion, met with
Italian political leaders during his first trip outside his country
in 18 years.
   Dubcek talked Friday with leading Socialists, including party
leader and former Prime Minister Bettino Craxi, and met with Nilde
Iotti, a Communist who is president of the Chamber of Deputies, the
lower house of Parliament.
   He also met leaders of several parties' parliamentary delegations.
   Dubcek was removed from the Czechoslovak Communist Party and
assigned to a lowly bureaucratic job after the Warsaw Pact invasion
crushed his ``Prague Spring.'' He had tried to institute reforms to
liberalize Czechoslovak politics and the economy.
   Iotti greeted Dubcek with the words, ``We have followed you
during all these years even when little was said about you,''
according to the Italian news agency ANSA. ``You represented the
courage of the truth and liberty and for this we honor you.''
   Dubcek traveled to Italy to receive an honorary degree from the
University of Bologna.
</TEXT>
