</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Three Unions At Eastern Seek To Block Sale of Shuttle to Trump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three unions at Eastern Airlines have sought a
preliminary injunction to block the $365 million sale of its
Northeast shuttle to real estate magnate Donald Trump.
   The motion filed Friday in U.S. District Court by the
International Association of Machinists, the Air Line Pilots
Association and Local 553 of the Transport Workers Union had been
anticipated for a month.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker in October had scheduled a
hearing on it for Dec. 2, giving Eastern until Nov. 25 to file a
response.
   The three unions contend that the sale of the Boston-New
York-Washington shuttle violates the Railway Labor Act as part of an
attempt by Eastern's parent, Texas Air Corp., to break the unions in
the midst of collective bargaining on new contracts.
   ``The sale is yet another attempt by (Texas Air Chairman) Frank
Lorenzo to dismantle Eastern Airlines,'' said Jack Bavis, head of
the pilots' union at the carrier.
   Although the shuttle has been consistently profitable, Texas Air
contends the sale is necessary to raise cash for preserving the rest
of Eastern, which has lost more than $300 million since 1986.
   The shuttle deal is scheduled for completion Dec. 15.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Legislation Authorizing $11.2 Billion for NASA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has signed legislation
authorizing $11.2 billion for the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration and re-creating a National Space Council, an advisory
group dissolved after the Nixon years.
   The legislation signed Friday includes $900 million to begin work
on a space station, of which $515 million must be cleared by George
Bush by May 15.
   The legislation gives the new president a say on whether to
proceed with the space station. NASA plans to ask for $2.1 billion
in fiscal 1990 and a Bush go-ahead would indicate the new
administration's commitment to build the $24 billion station.
   Reagan two years ago vetoed a NASA authorization bill and took
exception to a provision that would have re-established a National
Space Council in the president's office to advise him on
space-related matters. But on Friday, he signed the legislation
which does that very thing.
   There have been indications that Bush will name Vice
President-elect Dan Quayle to head the office.
   In opposing the space council earlier, Reagan said that ``besides
creating additional and unnecessary bureaucracy, the National Space
Council would duplicate the functions of the interagency bodies ...
that already coordinate the development and implementation of space
policy.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Atwater Promises Quick GOP Start On 1990 Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Atwater, tapped by President-elect George
Bush to take over the Republican National Committee, says the party
will start work immediately on the 1990 campaign.
   ``There's all kinds of races going on,'' Atwater noted Friday,
saying he especially wants to start recruiting for the midterm
congressional elections.
   While the Republicans have captured the White House in five of
the last six elections, they have not been able to gain control of
Congress. All of the House and one-third of the Senate seats are up
in 1990.
   The Republican National Committee meets in January to pick a new
chairman to succeed Frank Fahrenkopf, and Bush's endorsement
virtually guarantees that Atwater will be elected.
   Atwater, who managed Bush's campaign, said he has started making
peace with the other Republicans who ran for the party's
presidential nomination.
   Atwater said he plans to launch a program to recruit more blacks,
Hispanics and Asians to join the party, but he did not specify how
this would be carried out. GOP leaders for years have said they want
more minorities to become Republicans, but so far that has not
happened.
</TEXT>
