<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     11-19 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules No Cause For Holding 16 Opposition Activists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appellate tribunal ruled there was
no cause to keep holding 16 opposition activists jailed since July
after an anti-government demonstration turned violent, state-run
radio said.
   The Voice of Nicaragua broadcast said the 16 were ``absolved of
blame'' Friday on charges that included violating state security
laws. It did not say when they would be freed.
   Thirty-eight people were arrested after police violently broke up
a July 10 demonstration sponsored by the opposition Nicaraguan
Democratic Coordinate in Nandaimes, about 40 miles south of Managua,
the capital.
   Voice of Nicaragua said proceedings against nine detainees were
``provisionally suspended,'' but did not elaborate.
   It said proceedings against the remaining 13 activists were
continuing in Granada, about 27 miles east of Managua.
   Among those still subject to trial were Carlos Huembes, the
coordinate's president; Roger Guevara, its secretary-general; Miriam
Arguello, a leader of the Nicaraguan Conservative Party, and
Augustin Jarquin, a Social Democratic Party leader.
   Jarquin, Arguello and Social Democrat Marcos Herrera were freed
on bail Tuesday after suffering medical problems while in detention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881119-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 0221EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Nuclear     11-19 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Nuclear,Bjt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0404,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Order Speeding Nuclear Licensing Process</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores Bjt designation to slugline; SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng:
``The principle...'' to fix spelling of `principal' and `OK'd';
picks up 4th graf pvs, bgng: ``The operation...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has signed an executive order
aimed at speeding the nuclear-plant licensing process by giving a
federal agency sweeping new powers to carry out evacuation plans for
disputed nuclear power plants.
   White House officials issued no statements Friday beyond the
four-page order signed by the president, although the question of
expanding the authority of the Federal Emergency Management Agency
had been debated within the administration for months.
   The principal aim of the order is to help utilities get operating
licenses in instances where community opposition has held up
approval of evacuation plans. The plans must be OK'd by the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission before a license is granted.
   The operation of two plants, Shoreham on Long Island, N.Y., and
Seabrook in New Hampshire, has been stalled because state and local
governments, responding to community pressures, have refused to
submit evaucation plans to the NRC.
   Reagan's order substantially changes the role of FEMA in
emergency planning for nuclear plants and gives the agency virtual
police powers during actual radiological emergencies.
   The agency ``shall make all necessary plans and arrangements to
ensure that the federal government is prepared to assume any and all
functions and undertakings necessary to provide adequate protection
to the public ...,'' the order said, in part.
   Before licensing battles over Shoreham and Seabrook, state
governments had been required to submit acceptable evacuation plans
as part of the NRC licensing process. State and local opposition to
both plants led the NRC to accept plans submitted by their
utility-owners. But both plans face challenges on grounds that
utilities lack the police powers to carry them out in a genuine
crisis.
   Reagan's order addresses that problem by empowering FEMA to carry
out plans.
   Seabrook, finished two years ago, has been stalled for lack of
required emergency plans, principally because Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis refuses to cooperate.
   Ron Sher, a spokesman for New Hampshire Yankee, the company that
operates Seabrook, said in a telephone interview that he did not
believe the order was signed principally to benefit Seabrook.
   New Hampshire, under Gov. John Sununu, long ago submitted an
emergency plan for 17 of its communities near the plant. But owners
have had to submit plans for six nearby Massachusetts communities
that have refused to participate in emergency planning. They claim
the public safety could not be assured in case of a major accident.
   ``We just find it hard to believe that there's much in this plan
that would help us right now,'' Sher said in the interview. ``Maybe
it would have two years ago.''
   Earlier this year, Sununu had vehemently denied that he had been
pushing for the order to get the Seabrook plant into operation.
Sununu was named this week as White House chief of staff for
President-elect George Bush.
   Sununu's spokesman, Edward Lecius, denied in June that Sununu had
helped originate the order.
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., and Rep. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., who
oppose the order, had said earlier this year that they were
pessimistic about defeating it. Gregg won the New Hampshire
governor's race last week to succeed Sununu.
   Paul McEachern, a Democratic critic of Seabrook who lost to Gregg
for the governorship, said the order was a foregone conclusion.
   ``I believe they decided not to do anything until after the
election,'' McEachern said. ``The circumstantial evidence is
overwhelming that was the case, that they would get it signed at the
first appropriate time after the election.''
   Critics called the order a major change, even in advance of its
signing by Reagan.
   ``It's a major change in FEMA's role. ... It makes them judge and
jury of the plan,'' said anti-Seabrook attorney Matthew Brock.
   Jerry Mikorenda, a spokesman for the owner of the Shoreham plant,
Long Island Lighting Co., said Reagan's order ``resolves questions
of legal authority'' and ``reaffirms our position,'' though he said
the utility will continue with its plan to sell and close the plant.
   Terry Lynam, spokesman for New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, said the
governor was not surprised by the order ``because the (Reagan)
administration is determined to get the plant open.'' Cuomo is
opposed to the licensing of Shoreham.
   In a separate action, Reagan on Friday signed an executive order
establishing a nine-member President's Commission on Catastrophic
Nuclear Accidents to study ways to fully compensate victims of such
an accident beyond the limit of public liability called for by
Congress. The commission _ which is to file its report to Congress
by Aug. 20, 1990 _ also is to recommend any changes in laws and
rules necessary for the prompt, proper payment of valid damage
claims, as well as recommend any procedures needed to handle such
claims.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881119-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 0127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-L'Ambiance-OSHA     11-19 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-L'Ambiance-OSHA,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OSHA Drops Record $5.1 Million In Fines Against L'Ambiance
Contractors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal safety officials have agreed to
forgive the record $5.1 million in fines they levied against five
companies involved in building L'Ambiance Plaza, which collapsed and
killed 28 people, according to a published report.
   The Hartford Courant reported in Saturday's editions that
representatives of the Occupational Safety and Health Administration
agreed to drop the fines Friday after meeting all day with a
mediation panel seeking to settle litigation stemming from the
building's collapse.
   Instead, the federal agency will accept $430,000, the cost of its
investigation into the construction accident, The Courant reported.
   The apartment building was under construction when it collapsed
on April 23, 1987, killing 28 men and injuring 16.
   After the collapse, OSHA levied the $5.1 million in fines, citing
the project's contractors with willful violations of safety
regulations.
   Fined were Texstar Construction Corp., $2.5 million;
TPMI-Macomber, $2.5 million; and three smaller firms for lesser
amounts.
   Terry Mikelson, a spokesman for OSHA in Washington, comfirmed
Friday that a settlement had been reached in the fines, but he
declined to release any specifics.
</TEXT>
