<2ND_LINE>PM-OAS,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Delegate Abstains On OAS Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Organization of American
States committee approved a proposal to provide more diplomatic
rights to Latin ambassadors of the Washington-based organization.
The U.S. delegate abstained.
   Richard T. McCormack walked out of an OAS committee session after
clashing over the resolution Friday with Carlos Tunnerman,
Nicaragua's ambassador to the OAS. Diplomats viewed the resolution
as a product of the Tunnerman's expulsion from the United States in
July.
   Tunnerman was Nicaragua's ambassador to the United States when he
and seven other Nicaraguan diplomats were expelled from Washington
in retaliation for Nicaragua's expulsion of U.S. Ambassador Richard
Melton and seven U.S. diplomats.
   Nicaragua at the time claimed Melton was working to destabilize
the leftist government, a charge denied by Melton.
   The resolution approved Friday calls for study of amendments to
agreements between the OAS and the United States to provide more
diplomatic rights for Latin American representatives to the
31-member OAS.
   The full OAS General Assembly meets later today to approve all
committee resolutions.
   McCormack said he had no objections to the resolution, but added,
``The United States has the sovereign right'' to control entry to
the United States by OAS representatives.
   Tunnerman responded by criticizing ``the abusive way'' in which
the Reagan administration expelled him from the United States.
   Earlier Friday, an OAS committee approved an Inter-American Human
Rights Commission report that singled out Chile, Paraguay, El
Salvador, Cuba, Nicaragua and Guatemala for human rights abuses.
</TEXT>
