<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Jonestown-Cemetery Bjt   11-19 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jonestown-Cemetery, Bjt,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jonestown Victims Remembered At Graveside Memorial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A simple gray headstone marks the graves
of 409 people in a cemetery overlooking San Francisco Bay,
representing nearly half of the 913 people who died in the Jonestown
mass suicide a decade ago.
   As they have every year, friends and relatives of the Jonestown
victims gathered at the site Friday for a memorial service on the
anniversary of the deaths at the Peoples Temple jungle compound in
Guyana in South America.
   ``It's taken me a long time to get enough courage to come,'' said
Kim Dutra, one of 40 people who attended the service. She carried a
bouquet of red roses to the site where her mother, Beverly, is
buried.
   ``You know, sometimes the best thing to do is just put it behind
you.''
   Dutra's mother and 13-year-old brother were among the 912
followers of the Rev. Jim Jones who died along with him at Jonestown
on Nov. 18, 1978. Most committed suicide by drinking a poison-laced
beverage.
   The mass suicide came hours after church loyalists killed a U.S.
congressman, three journalists and a temple defector who had flown
to the complex to investigate complaints of abuse and tyranny there.
   Many of the dead were cremated or buried in family cemeteries.
The 409 bodies buried at Evergreen Cemetery could not be
individually identified because no fingerprints or other records
were available in the United States.
   Eddie Norwood recalled how his mother, who was not a Temple
member, kept him hidden from his father and other family members who
did belong to the cult. She feared Jones was psychotic and
dangerous, and feared he would have the child kidnapped to join the
church.
   ``I was hurt and I did not know then, but I know now,'' said
Norwood, who was 8 years old when 27 members of his family died at
Jonestown.
   On Friday, he joined his mother, Jynona Norwood, and other
relatives at the cemetery.
   One of their relatives, Fred Lewis, stood by the grave as the
service began, clutching a banner that read: ``10 Yr Jonestown
Memorial. We Will Not Forget.'' Breaking into tears, Lewis told the
gathering that he never had the emotional strength to talk at other
memorial services.
   ``This is the first time it happened that I've been able to cope
with the situation,'' he said later. ``I feel good and I'm happy,
I'm very happy to see so many people out here today.''
   Jynona Norwood, an evangelist who organizes the memorial each
year, said Jones offered a utopian world that provided food,
clothing, shelter and a form of religious solace to a wide spectrum
of people: poor minorities from the ghetto, pimps, prostitutes as
well as the average person on the street.
   ``The people at Jonestown were people who loved other people,
they weren't crazy,'' she said.
   But, Norwood said, a power-hungry Jones abused their trust and
faith, demanding absolute loyalty through sadistic mind-control
techniques. Peoples Temple turned out to be another cult, she said.
   Under pressure from allegations of misconduct, Jones moved most
of his Peoples Temple from San Francisco to Guyana, the only
English-speaking country in South America, in 1977. The cult leader
believed he would be safe from what he perceived as media and police
persecution.
   Yolanda Williams, a Peoples Temple member who left Guyana about
four months before the deaths, said, ``When I left it was with a
measure of hope for them (those remaining) _ that maybe we would
have a prayer.''
   Today, she said, she still lives in fear that a Jones loyalist
will hunt her down for speaking out against the Temple.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
