<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OldestPerson 1stLd-Writethru a0443 11-19 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oldest Person, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0443,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tobacco-Chewing 114-Year-Old Woman World's Oldest Person</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to recast; ADDS nature of illness in 15th
graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALATKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A band, a huge birthday cake and greetings
from presidents past, present and future helped Carrie White
celebrate her achievement: living to age 114, making her the world's
oldest person.
   Mrs. White also received a citation from the ``Guinness Book of
World Records'' during the celebration Friday under a large blue and
white tent at Putnam Memorial Nursing Home.
   Mrs. White, dressed in a pink dress and pink hat, sat in a
wheelchair, clutched a stuffed doll and shielded her eyes from the
glare of television lights and photographers' flashes.
   David Banks, head of the company that owns the nursing home,
where Mrs. White lives, presented her with a certificate from the
Guinness book.
   ``What's that?'' she asked faintly as it was placed on her tray.
   ``She's very aware what today is about and she dotes on attention
and hamming it up for the cameras,'' said Marjorie Allen, her
guardian.
   She said Mrs. White has a passion for Coca-Cola and chews Red Man
tobacco.
   ``Carrie White World's Oldest Person'' was written in frosting on
the cake, which featured 114 candles, a small globe and two
hourglasses.
   Several letters from well-wishers were read to a crowd of about
500 people, many of them her nursing home companions.
   Letters came from President Reagan, President-elect George Bush,
former Presidents Jimmy Carter and Gerald Ford, and Florida Gov. Bob
Martinez.
   ``Happy Birthday! How exciting to celebrate your 114th birthday.
That is quite an achievement,'' said the letter from Bush.
   Palatka Mayor Tim Smith proclaimed Friday ``Carrie White Day''
and said she was one of the few people who had a chance to be ``a
teen-ager twice in a lifetime.''
   Mrs. White was born in rural Gadsen County in 1874, just nine
years after the end of the Civil War.
   In London, Guinness spokeswoman Anna Nicholas said Friday, ``We
have a lot of original proof, so as much as we can ever be sure,
she's the oldest person.''
   Ms. Nicholas said that since Mrs. White was hospitalized for many
years starting in 1909 for post-typhoid psychosis, she has ``medical
documentation that goes way back.'' Guinness also sends researchers
to check on such claims and has an expert in Britain who looks at
the evidence, she said.
   Karl Dalke, chief of research for the Florida Department of
Health and Rehabilitative Services, said the Social Security
Administration also verified Mrs. White's age as 114.
   Mrs. White will have to wait at least a year before her name
appears in the record book because the 1989 edition has already gone
to press, said assistant editor Cyd Smith in New York.
   According to the Guinness records, the greatest authenticated age
to which any human has ever lived is 120 years, 237 days. Shigechiyo
Izumi of Asan, Tokunoshima Island, Japan, was born June 19, 1865,
and died Feb. 21, 1986.
   Mrs. White is three months older than Jeanne Calmet of Arles,
France, who was listed as the world's oldest person in this year's
edition of the book.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881119-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 0419EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HealthCosts 1stLd-Writethru a0407 11-19 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Health Costs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0407,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation's Health Bill Jumped Nearly 10 Percent Last Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``The annual...'' to delete extra
word; SUBS 10th graf pvs, bgng: ``Measured as...'' to add details;
picks up 11th graf pvs, bgng: ``Health spending...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's health care costs jumped 9.8
percent last year to $500.3 billion, or $1,987 for every man, woman
and child, a federal report says.
   The annual report issued Friday by the Health Care Financing
Administration highlighted one of the major challenges facing the
incoming Bush administration: how to insure health care for an aging
population during a time when spending on Medicare and Medicaid is
already a major contributor to the national debt.
   The popular conception is that Medicare is self-financed by
Social Security payroll deductions paid by retired and current
workers.
   The reality is that 75 percent of the money to pay for the
fastest growing part of the program _ doctor services _ comes
straight from the treasury.
   All of the federal share of Medicaid _ states pay about half _
comes from the treasury.
   Medicare and the federal share of Medicaid accounted for $144.7
billion of the nation's total health bill in 1987, an increase of
8.9 percent from calendar 1986.
   Largely because of cost containment programs instituted by the
Reagan administration, the federal increase was substantially less
than the 11.7 percent increase for state and local spending and the
9.8 percent rise for private spending.
   Still, federal health spending in calendar 1987 was more than
double the $71 billion it was the year before Reagan took office in
1981.
   State and local health spending amounted to $62.7 billion in 1987
and the private share was $293 billion.
   Measured as a part of the overall economy, the $500.3 billion in
total health spending consumed a record 11.1 percent of the Gross
National Product in 1987, up from 10.7 percent in 1986. GNP
represents the total of all goods and services produced in the
economy. The health care costs work out to an average of $1,987 for
every man, woman and child.
   Health spending was 9.1 percent of GNP the year before Reagan
took office and 5.9 percent in 1965, before the advent of Medicare
and Medicaid.
   ``Providing effective health care at affordable cost is a major
challenge confronting our society,'' said Dr. William L. Roper, the
HCFA administrator whose agency oversees Medicare and Medicaid.
   Noting that Medicare and Medicaid are the largest single payers
of medical bills _ accounting for 28.9 percent of all spending _
Roper said, ``It is imperative that we identify the most effective
means of providing health care to avoid unnecessary and duplicate
procedures.''
   The various state and local programs paid a total of 12.5 percent
of medical costs in 1987 while millions of individuals and thousands
of private insurance companies paid the other 58.6 percent.
   The annual report, which normally comes out in the summer, was
delayed this year because HCFA actuaries were occupied with changes
in Medicare and Medicaid, prompted by enactment of the catastrophic
health insurance measure, the largest single expansion of Medicare
in its two-decade history.
   The report is figured on a calendar year basis because it
incorporates private as well as public expenditures.
   Medicare expenditures alone were $79.9 billion in fiscal 1987 _
the government accounting period from Oct. 1, 1986 through Sept. 30,
1987 _ and increased 7.7 percent from fiscal 1986, a little less
than the overall 9.8 percent increase.
   Roper noted that programs to constrain the growth of hospital
charges resulted in an increase of less than 2 percent in Medicare
hospital spending in fiscal 1987 while payments for physicians'
services continued to grow at double-digit rates.
   ``Between fiscal year 1975 and fiscal year 1987, Medicare
physician spending per beneficiary increased at a compound annual
rate of 15 percent,'' Roper said in a statement accompanying the
report.
   ``Over the next 10 years, even without any program expansions, we
project that Medicare spending for physicians' services will
triple,'' said Roper.
   He predicted that Medicare outlays will exceed the yearly
spending for Social Security within two decades.
   Counting both public and private spending, hospital care
accounted for 39 percent of total expenditures, physicians' services
20 percent and nursing homes 8 percent.
   The rest went for a variety of other expenses, such as medicines
purchased directly by individuals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
