<DOCNO> AP881119-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 0420EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Waite     11-19 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Waite,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speaker: Waite Release Separate From Iranian Influence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iranian parliament speaker said the
release of Anglican Church envoy Terry Waite is an issue separate
from Iran's influence in Lebanon, the official Islamic Republic News
Agency reported today.
   The news agency, monitored in Cyprus, said speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani was reacting to a report that Kenyan President Daniel
Arap Moi carried a message to Iranian leaders asking them to mediate
to gain Waite's release from Lebanon.
   Moi delivered the message from ``unidentified Christian
authorities,'' the agency said. Moi ended an official three-day
visit Thursday to Iran.
   The agency quoted Iranian press reports saying Rafsanjani
acknowledged that the Islamic Republic has ``sway in Lebanon'' but
that ``Terry Waite's release from captivity is simply another
issue.''
   Waite, 49, disappeared Jan. 20, 1987, after leaving his west
Beirut hotel to negotiate with Islamic Jihad, which has claimed to
hold kidnapped foreigners. No group claimed to hold Waite, but he is
widely believed to be held by Shiite Moslem militants.
   Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press, is the longest held of the 15 foreign hostages in
Lebanon. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Rafsanjani, who is also acting commander of the armed forces,
told university students in the southwestern provincial capital of
Ahwaz that Iran should pursue an independent foreign policy without
making enemies, the news agency said.
   The agency quoted him as saying Iran could have pursued such a
policy in the past without antagonizing countries such as Kuwait and
France. If Iran had demonstrated ``more tactfulness'' in dealing
with those two countries they might not have supported Iraq in the
Persian Gulf conflict, the agency said.
   ``Despite the inherent hostility with Islam in the Western world,
Iran is now in a position to make good on her previously crude
diplomacy,'' the agency quoted the speaker as saying.
   Rafsanjani also repeated that private business would play an
important role in postwar reconstruction. The Iran-Iraq war ended
Aug. 20 in a United Nations-brokered cease-fire, and since then
little progress has been reported in peace talks.
</TEXT>
