<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GOPGovernors     11-19 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GOP Governors,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republican Chiefs Say Bush Should Check Federal Spending To Ease
Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POINT CLEAR, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican governors gathering here
generally recommend spending cuts, not new taxes, as the medicine
President-elect George Bush should use to cure the federal budget
deficit.
   ``Clearly, expenditures have to be cut,'' New Mexico Gov. Garrey
Carruthers said.
   ``Taxes are still too high in this country,'' said Delaware Gov.
Michael N. Castle, the conference chairman.
   Both men are among nearly two dozen GOP chief executives planning
to attend the National Republican Governors Conference. The agenda
for the meeting, which runs today through Tuesday, features a speech
by the president-elect on the closing day.
   ``We need to continue to look for ways to reduce costs, to invest
in prevention-oriented solutions at the state level, to collect the
billions of (tax) dollars that are not being collected right now,''
Castle said.
   Carruthers and Castle made their comments in interviews before
the conference's start.
   Most of those interviewed called for spending cuts or fiscal
restraint, and some promoted Bush's ``flexible freeze'' option in
suggesting ways to deal with the budget deficit left by the outgoing
Reagan administration.
   ``Cut spending, especially on the entitlement side,'' recommended
New Hampshire Gov.-elect Judd Gregg, who is succeeding the man Bush
has selected as his chief of staff, John Sununu. ``Go after the
COLAS (cost of living increases), don't believe anything (House
Speaker) Jim Wright has to say relative to the budget and don't make
deals.''
   ``I'm sure the president plans to handle it by continuing to
expand the economy and second, by working with Congress to reduce
the level of expenditure and set spending by priorities,'' said
Florida Gov. Bob Martinez, whose state will play host to the
governors Sunday on a tour of the USS Lexington at Pensacola.
   ``Controlling spending is critical to deficit reduction,'' said
Wisconsin Gov. Tommy G. Thompson, ``and the line-item veto authority
should be enacted to help our next president and the United States
succeed in reducing the federal deficit.''
   South Carolina Gov. Carroll Campbell, Maine Gov. John R. McKernan
and Iowa Gov. Terry E. Branstad were among those who mentioned a
``flexible freeze'' as an alternative.
   Campbell said such a freeze on spending could limit budget growth
to a percentage of the inflation rate, perhaps 1 percentage point
below the Consumer Price Index.
   Alabama Gov. Guy Hunt, the host for the conference and the first
Republican governor of Alabama this century, was the only GOP chief
executive to mention specifically a balanced budget constitutional
amendment.
   But whatever the solution, Hunt said, controlling the deficit
must be the highest priority of the new administration.
   Without it, he said, ``I don't think you can address the other
matters.''
   The number of Republican governors dropped from 23 to 22 with the
Nov. 8 election. Most plan to attend the Point Clear conference.
   The four-day agenda includes remarks by Sununu, Attorney General
Dick Thornburgh, Bush senior adviser Bob Teeter, campaign manager
Lee Atwater, New York Rep. Jack Kemp, Republican National Committee
Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf, Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos, and
University of Tennessee President Lamar Alexander, who served two
terms as governor of Tennessee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
