<DOCNO> AP881119-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 0505EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AT&TOutage     11-19 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AT&T Outage,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Coast Phone Service Disrupted As Crew Severs Cable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAYREVILLE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AT&T telephone service along the East
Coast was disrupted for about six hours when an underground
transmission cable was severed by a work crew, causing computer
problems as well as telephone outages.
   The trouble Friday was caused when a backhoe apparently severed
the 3-inch, fiber-optic cable at a railroad yard in Sayreville,
south of Newark.
   The accident forced massive rerouting of telephone calls that
ordinarily use the line, which carries about 200,000 calls an hour,
said AT&T District Manager Jim Nelson.
   ``It's almost like a highway in that you have to go along it to
get from, say, New York to Florida,'' said Nelson. ``This is a major
blockage affecting the whole East Coast.''
   The outage, which began at 12:15 p.m., was corrected by about
6:30 p.m. for most of the nation. However, service in areas near the
severed cable was still reported spotty late Friday.
   In addition to affecting phone service, private customers whose
computer networks use AT&T phone lines, including The Associated
Press wire service, experienced service problems Friday afternoon,
Nelson said.
   Harry Baumgartner, a spokesman for AT&T in Basking Ridge, said
calls between area codes on the East Coast were rerouted by AT&T's
computerized network, which relays calls along one of 14 lines in
other parts of the country according to the load on those other
regional systems.
   But not all calls were rerouted successfully. Many people
received a fast busy tone or a recording that indicated their call
could not go through, AT&T said.
   Baumgartner said it was impossible to estimate how many millions
of customers were affected by the problem.
   Fiber optic cables are composed of hair-thin strands of glass
that carry phone calls and data as pulses of light. They can
transmit many more calls than the traditional copper cables they are
replacing.
   The outage affected New Jersey Lottery ticket sales. Lottery
ticket machines were shut down from 12:15 p.m. until 9:30 p.m.
because of the telephone troubles, said lottery spokeswoman Sharon
A. Southard.
</TEXT>
