<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coast guard ships searched for a missing sailor in
rough seas off Okinawa where a Panamanian cargo ship sank early
today. Officials said at least two crewmen were dead.
   Passing tankers from Japan and Britain and a Japanese Maritime
Safety Agency vessel rescued 19 of the La Vie en Rose's 20 crew
members, said an official at the agency's office in Naha, Okinawa.
   Two of the rescued men died, and one crewman was still missing at
dusk, he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Earlier reports said 17 crew members were missing and feared dead.
   All 20 of the Filipino crewmen had abandoned the ship, another
official said.
   The La Vie en Rose radioed for help after it began taking on
water in stormy seas Friday night, he said. The ship sank at 12:42
a.m. today.
   The Taiwanese coast guard alerted Japanese authorities, who
dispatched a search plane and a ship to the area, 170 miles east of
Taiwan and near the Okinawan island chain.
   The ship was headed for northern Japan with a cargo of Malaysian
tropical timber when it began taking on water, officials said.
