<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Armenia     11-19 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Armenia,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikes Again Shut Transport, Factories In Armenian Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A protest strike in Armenia's capital shut down
public transport and most factories as residents continued to demand
unification with a predominantly Armenian region of a neighboring
republic, Pravda reported today.
   The Communist Party daily said the week-long general strike in
Yerevan was triggered by reports from the Nagorno-Karabakh region of
clashes between anti-riot police and Armenians that left seven
people hospitalized with injuries.
   Official media have reported no recent violence in
Nagorno-Karabakh, a part of the Soviet republic of Azerbaijan since
1923, and it was not immediately possible to contact residents by
telephone from Moscow today to check the reports.
   ``An absolute majority'' of Armenians who gathered on Yerevan's
Opera Square supported the general strike as a sign of solidarity
with the ethnic Armenian population of Nagorno-Karabakh, Pravda said.
   On Friday in Yerevan, Pravda said, ``beginning in the morning,
transport and the majority of factories and offices were not
working.'' There were also protest marches in the Armenian capital,
the newspaper said.
   Since February, Armenians in their republic and Nagorno-Karabakh
have been demanding the region be united with Armenia, and local
legislatures in both places approved the transfer of sovereignty.
   In July, the Supreme Soviet Presidium, the nation's top executive
body, refused to alter the region's status, citing Azerbaijan's
constitutional right to veto any change in its territorial status.
</TEXT>
