<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 0637EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Graham     11-19 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Graham,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hollywood Gossip Columnist, Fitzgerald Companion, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legendary gossip columnist Sheilah
Graham, who reported the loves and lives of Hollywood's most
glittering stars, has died of heart failure at age 84.
   Ms. Graham, who lived in this exclusive oceanfront resort, died
Thursday at Good Samaritan Hospital in West Palm Beach. She had
undergone two hip operations and suffered two heart attacks in
recent years, said her friend Celia Lipton Farris.
   ``She's the last of the great era that wrote about Hollywood
stars,'' said Ms. Farris.
   Raised in an orphanage, Ms. Graham found fame and fortune through
sheer pluck. Along the way she wrote 11 books and was romantically
involved with flamboyant Jazz Age novelist F. Scott Fitzgerald.
   With fellow columnists Louella Parsons and Hedda Hopper, she
formed what followers called the ``Unholy Trio,'' and captured
Hollywood's juiciest gossip in a no-holds-barred style.
   ``Joan Crawford had no right to be a mother,'' she once wrote in
the syndicated column she filed for 40 years. ``She was a
perfectionist and expected it of her children. She was always
cleaning something.''
   Ms. Graham reported on the time Bonzo the chimp nearly strangled
Ronald Reagan with his own tie, and the time Marilyn Monroe sang
``Happy Birthday'' to John F. Kennedy in Madison Square Garden.
   But her own life was as controversial as the people she wrote
about.
   Born Lily Sheil in London's East End on Sept. 15, 1904, Ms.
Graham at age 18 married a salesman 25 years her senior before
trying careers as a serious actress and a chorus girl.
   In 1933, she emigrated to New York to make her fortune. After
reporting for New York papers for two years, she left for Hollywood,
where she was courted by Howard Hughes and John Wayne and later met
Fitzgerald.
   Their affair ended after three years when Fitzgerald died of a
heart attack in 1940, collapsing at her feet. Ms. Farris said she
still frequently spoke of him, once lamenting: ``I won't be
remembered for my writing. I'll be remembered as Scott's mistress.''
   Ms. Graham's autobiography, ``Beloved Infidel,'' was later made
into a movie starring Deborah Kerr and Gregory Peck.
   Ms. Graham's survivors include a daughter, Wendy Fairey, a son,
Robert Westbrook, and three grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881119-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 0639EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hirohito     11-19 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hirohito,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito, Down To 66 Pounds, Sleeps Through A Visit By His Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito, down to 66 pounds since he became
seriously ill two months ago, is so weak that he slept through a
visit today by his son, palace officials said.
   The 87-year-old emperor has had no sign of blood discharges for
10 days, the longest such period since he fell ill with an
intestinal hemorrhage, the officials said. They reported him in
stable but weak condition.
   Imperial Household Agency spokesman Kenji Maeda said Hirohito
slept through a visit by Crown Prince Akihito and his family,
although the emperor awoke later in the day.
   Doctors say they sometimes cannot tell if Hirohito is asleep or
awake, and that he sleeps much of the time. Reports Friday said he
had lost 37 pounds from his normal weight and is down to 66 pounds.
Maeda said his strength is waning and he speaks infrequently.
   Hirohito has received 42 pints in blood transfusions since the
onset of his illness.
   Palace officials refuse to comment on reports that Hirohito has
cancer.
</TEXT>
