<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingTeen-Agers     11-19 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Teen-Agers,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Acknowledges Barricade Gap, But Many Questions Remain In
Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials acknowledge there was a
gap between concrete road barricades on a closed road where a car
plunged into a river, killing all four occupants, but they don't
know if anyone is to blame.
   Officials said Friday they did not know who moved the 2-ton
concrete barriers that would have prevented the car from going into
the water, or when they were pushed apart.
   The car was found by police divers in the Mill River on Thursday,
five days after four young friends from East Lyme disappeared during
a night out in New Haven. Their disappearance prompted a nationwide
search.
   Divers searched the river bottom after a patrolman noticed the
gap Wednesday, and public works crews closed the opening.
   The four victims drowned, the state medical examiner's office
said.
   Police said a case of mostly empty beer cans was found in the
car. But they said they did not know whether the results of
blood-alcohol tests would be released because they hadn't determined
who was driving.
   Police also were checking reports that the four, all under the
legal drinking age of 21, were served alcohol in several bars the
night they disappeared.
   Killed in the accident were three 19-year-olds, Laura
Lagrotteria, who worked at a pizza parlor; Jill Sawyer, a student at
the University of Rhode Island; and Christy Stevens, a student at
Mohegan Community College in Norwich; and Michael Gallo, 20, a
student at Southern Connecticut State University in New Haven.
   The accident occurred on a dark stretch of road that was closed
last year because a 105-year-old pivoting bridge along it was beyond
repair. The bridge was left in its open position, parallel to the
river, so boats could pass by on either side.
   Mayor Biagio DiLieto and other city officials told reporters at a
news conference Friday that an investigation had confirmed that the
concrete road barriers at the open bridge had been moved, leaving a
gap wide enough for a car to pass through.
   One or more of the three 2-ton concrete blocks were out of place
when the car drove into the river, city officials said.
   The officials' claim that they had received no public complaints
about a gap in the barricade was disputed by a radio station's
traffic reporter, who said he passed on complaints from motorists
several times since March.
   Police found the blocks out of position after an Oct. 22 car
accident at the site, but city officials said they were not sure how
big a gap existed at that time. The accident was the third at the
barriers since the bridge was closed in August 1987.
   City officials said they are investigating why public works crews
put up wooden barriers after the Oct. 22 accident instead of
returning the blocks to their original position. Two barrier
stanchions were recovered from the river.
   Authorities also are investigating whether a detour sign was
incorrectly placed to send traffic down the closed street the night
of the crash. The sign was found in the incorrect position Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
