<DOCNO> AP881119-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 0725EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Egypt-PLO 1stLd-Writethru   11-19 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0464,0723</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mubarak Says Egypt Recognizes Palestinian State</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with details, quotes, Syrian-backed guerrilla
leader rejecting declaration. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak said today that Egypt
recognizes the newly proclaimed Palestinian state and that PLO
leader Yasser Arafat will visit Cairo for talks on Middle East peace
strategy.
   Mubarak's announcement brought the number of countries
recognizing an independent Palestinian nation to 32.
   It was not immediately known whether the Egyptian recognition
would lead to diplomatic relations and the establishment of a
Palestinian embassy in Cairo.
   The PLO has an office in Cairo, but its mission is listed in the
Foreign Ministry's Diplomatic List in an annex separate from embassy
listings. The head of the mission is not an ambassador and does not
present credentials to the president.
   Egyptian recognition was certain to irritate Israel, which has
diplomatic relations with Egypt under their 1979 peace treaty, the
only one between an Arab country and the Jewish state. Israel
reacted angrily to recognition of the Palestinian state by Turkey
this week.
   Israel today had no immediate reaction to Mubarak's remarks. A
Foreign Ministry official said the reports from Cairo would be
checked before any response was made.
   Israel has mounted a diplomatic offensive against international
recognition of the Palestinian state. Foreign Minister Shimon Peres
kicked it off Friday in a meeting with 60 diplomats from 42
countries.
   The Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile and
the policy-making body of the Palestine Liberation Organization,
declared an independent Palestinian homeland at its meeting in
Algiers.
   The independence declaration did not define the boundaries of the
future state, saying it would be determined by future negotiations.
   Col. Saeed Moussa, a Syrian-backed Palestinian leader, has called
for the creation of new PLO to replace Arafat's ``capitulationist
command,'' a Beirut newspaper reported today.
   Moussa, better known by the code-name of Abu Moussa, was quoted
by the independent daily An-Nahar as saying the council's
recognition of U.N. Security Council resolutions 242 and 338 was
tantamount to treason.
   ``The resolutions carry implicit recognition of Israel,'' Moussa
was quoted as saying.
   A new PLO command, Moussa was quoted as saying, ``will carry out
the armed struggle against the Zionist enemy (Israel) until our
homeland is liberated.''
   Moussa broke from Arafat's PLO in 1983 and set up headquarters
for his Fatah-Uprising faction in the Syrian capital.
   Mubarak's statement appeared to upgrade two previous official
position statements, which expressed support for the Palestinian
state and termed the endorsement ``stronger than recognition.''
   ``Some countries cast doubts on our position when we said that we
supported the resolutions of the Palestine National Council and said
we did not recognize (the Palestinian state),'' Mubarak said in the
Nile Delta city of Benha.
   ``This is our cause. We are saying that we supported all the
council's resolutions, and this includes recognition of the
Palestinian state.''
   There was no explanation of the upgrading today of Cairo's
position to explicit recognition.
   Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin told Israel Television
last Wednesday that if Egypt recognized the Palestinian state, it
would be ``deviating'' from the Camp David peace framework accords
concluded with Israel.
   The U.S.-mediated Camp David agreements provided for negotiations
to determine the final status of the Israeli-occupied West Bank and
Gaza, where about 1.5 million Palestinians live. Rabin said
``unilateral action'' would breach that aspect of the accords.
   Mubarak said: ``I shall hear from Yasser Arafat about details of
the Palestinian council's resolutions when he visits Cairo. We also
will discuss future steps.''
   Egyptian newspapers reported Arafat was expected in Cairo today
for the opening of a five-day symposium on ``protection of religious
shrines and cultural heritage in Palestine.''
   Abdullah al-Hourani, a member of the PLO Executive Committee who
is attending the symposium, told reporters Arafat was unable to
arrive in time for the opening session but hoped to come ``within
the next few days.''
   The nations to have recognized the Palestinian state are:
Afghanistan, Algeria, Bahrain, Bangladesh, Cuba, Cyprus, Egypt,
Gambia, India, Indonesia, Iraq, Jordan, Kuwait, Lebanon, Libya,
Madagascar, Malaysia, Mauritania, Morocco, Nicaragua, North and
South Yemen, Qatar, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Senegal, Singapore,
Sudan, Tunisia, Turkey, the United Arab Emirates and Yugoslavia.
</TEXT>
