<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0461 11-19 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0461,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms in Arkansas, Tennessee, Ohio Valley; Snow In New
Mexico</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting 1st Ld; Subs 5th graf, `Rain and ...' to give
location of Gallup, N.M., in western part of state. Picks up 6th
graf, `Snow also ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms with heavy rains and gusty winds lingered in parts
of Arkansas, Tennessee and the lower Ohio Valley today, and snow
blanketed eastern New Mexico.
   The storms in Arkansas pelted Little Rock with 7 inches of rain,
breaking the city's previous record of 1.91 inches for the date
Friday.
   Heavy rains produced reports of flooding in several Arkansas
counties, where high water forced the closing of some roads.
   Strong winds blew down trees, damaged a public school's roof and
a mobile home, and downed power lines in various Arkansas
municipalities.
   Rain and some snow developed in eastern New Mexico. By Friday
evening, 9 inches of snow had fallen at Gallup in western New Mexico.
   Snow also fell in the southern foothills of the Colorado Rockies,
leaving up to 5 inches.
   A band of snow developed from southwest Minnesota into northwest
Wisconsin. Up to 4 inches was expected today.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms in eastern
Texas, the lower Mississippi Valley and the Tennessee Valley;
thunderstorms, possibly severe, from eastern Texas across Louisiana
and southern Arkansas into western Mississippi; rain spreading
across the central Appalachians, the Ohio Valley, the Great Lakes
states, the middle Mississippi Valley, eastern Kansas and Oklahoma;
snow from the Oklahoma Panhandle to western Kansas and from southern
Minnesota to northwest Wisconsin; and rain and mountain snow in the
Pacific Northwest.
   Predicted highs: upper 20s to near 32 degrees from northern
Minnesota across North Dakota and eastern Montana; mid-30s to the
40s from New England across the Great Lakes to the upper Mississippi
Valley, as well as South Dakota, the central Plains, Oklahoma, the
Texas Panhandle, the Rockies, and the Pacific Northwest; 50s to low
70s in California and the desert Southwest; and 70s and low 80s in
southeast Texas, the central Gulf of Mexico states and Florida. The
rest of the nation should generally be in the 50s and 60s.
   The nation's temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 3 degrees at
Devils Lake, N.D., to 80 degrees at Homestead (Fla.) Air Force Base
and Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 55 cloudy; Boston 38 fair; Buffalo 31 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 57 cloudy; Cincinnati 40 rain; Cleveland 45 cloudy;
Detroit 44 cloudy; Miami 79 fair; New York 38 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 40 fair; Portland, Maine 28 fair; Washington 42 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 8 snow; Chicago 45 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
55 foggy; Denver 25 partly cloudy; Des Moines 44 cloudy;
Indianapolis 44 cloudy; Kansas City 46 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul
37 cloudy; Nashville 50 cloudy; New Orleans 74 foggy; St. Louis 44
drizzle.
   _West: Albuquerque 33 cloudy; Anchorage 11 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 48 fair; Los Angeles 53 fair; Phoenix 47 fair; Salt Lake City
26 fair; San Diego 52 fair; San Francisco 50 partly cloudy; Seattle
46 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 25 fair; Toronto 28 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
