<1ST_LINE>r a PM-B-1BCrash     11-19 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-B-1B Crash,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomber In South Dakota Crash Passed Inspection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAFKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The B-1B bomber that crashed at Ellsworth
Air Force Base had passed a three-hour inspection ordered for the
fleet after another B-1B bomber crashed in Texas, Air Force
officials said.
   Brig. Gen. Robert Marquette Jr. said Thursday's crash probably
will not force another grounding of the nation's fleet of advanced
jet bombers.
   Marquette, commander of the 12th Air Division at Ellsworth, said
Friday that a permanent team is being assembled to study the crash.
   The four crewmen parachuted to safety Thursday night, but the
$280 million plane was destroyed after smashing onto a runway at
Ellsworth during a routine training flight. One crew member suffered
a back injury.
   ``The crew is in relatively good shape,'' Marquette said.
   Thursday's crash came two days after officials reported that the
Air Force had inspected and cleared more than two-thirds of the 98
B-1B bombers, which were grounded briefly after the Nov. 8 crash
that destroyed a plane in Texas.
   The plane that crashed Thursday was cleared for flight on Monday.
   Marquette said air operations at Ellsworth have been suspended
until the debris has been fully examined.
   Marquette refused to speculate on the cause of the crash, but
said there was no evidence of an engine fire.
   The bomber was trying to land when it crashed at 10:40 p.m.,
toppling a utility pole that cut off power to two schools and a
residential area.
   The Washington Post, in today's editions, quoted sources as
saying preliminary reports indicated the pilot misjudged his
approach and was preparing to land far short of the Ellsworth
runway. The paper's sources said it was unclear whether the
miscalculation resulted from a human error or a malfunction in the
bomber's sophisticated flight aid systems.
   The newspaper's sources said the pilot, realizing a crash was
imminent, pulled the nose of the plane up, giving the crew time to
eject safely.
   The Post also reported that sources said initial reports
suggested that the B-1B crash in Texas was caused by a broken fuel
line that spewed fuel over the engine, causing it to burst into
flames.
</TEXT>
