<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     11-19 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How many city workers does it take to screw in a
light bulb?
   About two dozen if you have 19,800 light bulbs, the Parks
Department here found out.
   To light up the city's new Westlake Park for the holidays, the
department ordered 792 strings of Christmas lights, each with 25
bulbs _ but the strands came with 25 empty sockets.
   The Chicago supplier shipped the bulbs separately so they
wouldn't break, said Jeff Sandoz, an administrative assistant in the
department.
   Sandoz handed out bulbs and strands to fellow workers for several
days, and about 7,800 bulbs had been installed during staff meetings
and by receptionists between phone calls.
   About two dozen Parks Department employees met in a city
cafeteria for an hour and a half Thursday to screw in the last
12,000 bulbs or so.
   Next week, a Christmas tree will be lit at Westlake Center, along
with the strands of lights at the adjacent park _ thanks to lots of
finger-twisting by city workers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some city employees have been seeing
less of each other in the past few months, but not because they're
staying away from work.
   It's just that there's less of them to see.
   City Assessor George Bratcher decided in March that he needed to
drop some of his 215 pounds. When he succeeded in getting down to
155, he inspired some fellow employees.
   Finance Director Stanley Chubinski lost 25 pounds with his diet.
``I plan on starting it again after Thanksgiving,'' he said.
   Another employee who is putting off dieting until after the
holiday is account clerk Barbara Jones of the finance department.
She wants to lose another 10 pounds after Thanksgiving.
   ``In four weeks, I lost 14 pounds,'' she said. ``My doctor said I
should slow down a little, so I went to 3 pounds a week, then went
off it for a while.''
   ``Every week, someone new yells at me in the hall, `I've lost
another pound,''' Bratcher said.
   ``I'm on my third belt,'' he went on. ``All of my clothes have
been altered twice and are too big now, but I'm not going to alter
them again.''
</TEXT>
