<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 0807EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan-Nuclear-Reax 2ndLd-Writethru a0479 11-19 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Nuclear-Reax, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0479,0808</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Critics: Order Gives FEMA Police Power Utility Plans Don't Have</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 19th graf, `In the ...,' to change ``building'' to
``builder.''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan-Nuclear, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operator of the Seabrook nuclear power
plant says President Reagan's order allowing a federal agency to
devise evacuation plans for such plants comes too late to help that
troubled plant get a license.
   But Seabrook critics think the executive order will give
utility-written evacuation plans the authority they now lack.
   The order, signed Friday by Reagan, allows the Federal Emergency
Management Agency to develop and carry out evacution plans for
nuclear plants when state and local governments refuse to cooperate
in the emergency planning.
   The $5.7 billion Seabrook project, completed two years, has been
unable to win a commercial license due to opposition from
neighboring Massachusetts, where six communities fall within
Seabrook's 10-mile evacuation zone.
   Seabrook officials said Friday the order does not affect the
plant, because it already received federal permission to submit its
own evacuation plans for the Massachusetts communities.
   ``We just find it hard to believe that there's much in this plan
that would help us right now. Maybe it would have two years ago,''
said Ron Sher, a spokesman for New Hampshire Yankee, Seabrook's
operator.
   But Paul McEachern, a longtime Seabrook foe and the unsuccessful
Democratic gubernatorial candidate this year, said the major flaw in
utility-submitted plans is that utilities lack the authority to
effectively carry them out. The order, however, gives FEMA that
authority, he said.
   ``It fills that very large gap that's left with utility-sponsored
plans,'' McEachern said. ``Public Service Company of New Hampshire
(Seabrook's lead owner) doesn't have police powers in the state of
Massachusetts. FEMA can be empowered by the president for that.''
   The executive order was received skeptically by the Dukakis
administration in Massachusetts, which maintains that local
governments are best able to answer citizens' concerns about nuclear
safety.
   ``We can't comment specifically on the order because we haven't
seen it, but our position has been and continues to be that it is
state and local officials who know how to best protect our
citizens,'' Martie Barnes, a spokeswoman for Gov. Michael S.
Dukakis, said Friday in Boston.
   McEachern speculated that the Reagan administration anticipated
the legal challenge to Seabrook's evacuation plans by Massachusetts,
including the state's argument that Seabrook's owners lack the
authority to execute the plans.
   ``He wouldn't have signed the executive order unless he had to,
because it's going to be met with hostility from the New Hampshire
delegation,'' McEachern said.
   Gov.-elect Judd Gregg, an outgoing congressman, and Sen. Gordon
Humphrey, R-N.H., strongly opposed the order when it came to light
earlier this year. Neither returned telephone calls seeking comment
Friday night.
   Rep. Robert Smith, R-N.H., said the final version seems slightly
weaker than the wording in the original draft, ``much more
conciliatory.'' He said he supports the thrust of the order, because
he feels the federal government must step in when state or local
governments try to block a plant's licensing.
   Another Seabrook critic, Jane Doughty of the Seacoast
Anti-Pollution League, predicted a legal battle over the order.
   ``I'm sure the intervenors in the (Seabrook) case will do
something about it, because Congress did not change the laws, and
clearly they did not intend that the federal government should usurp
state and local planning,'' she said.
   Until recently, states were required to submit an acceptable
evacuation plan as part of the NRC licensing process. Because of
opposition to Seabrook by Massachusetts and to the Shoreham plant on
Long Island by New York Gov.Mario Cuomo, the NRC has accepted _ but
not approved _ evacuation plans for both plants written by their
utility owners. Both plans face legal challenges.
   Shoreham was completed in 1984 but never received a commercial
operating license because of the dispute over the evacuation plan.
   In the face of that, its builder, the Long Island Lighting Co.,
last spring reached a preliminary agreement with the state to
abandon the plant in return for the state's approval of a
compensation plan for the utility. That plan awaits action by the
New York Legislature.
   Jerry Mikorenda, a spokesman for LILCO, said Reagan's order
``resolves questions of legal authority'' and ``reaffirms our
position,'' though he said the utility will continue with its plan
to sell and close the plant.
   Terry Lynam, spokesman for New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, said the
governor was not surprised by the order ``because the (Reagan)
administration is determined to get the plant open.'' Cuomo is
opposed to the licensing of Shoreham.
   Lynam said Cuomo made his opposition to the pending executive
order known in an Aug. 4 letter to Reagan.
</TEXT>
