<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia 2ndLd-Writethru a0460 11-19 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0460,0806</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Of Thousands Serbs March Through Belgrade</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Milosevic speech, rival rallies in
Pristine, other details. ADDS laserphoto. No pickup.
^LaserPhoto PR1</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of thousands of chanting
Serbs rallied today to back demands by their ambitious Communist
Party leader Slobodan Milosevic for more control over the troubled
southern province of Kosovo.
   ``We will not give up Kosovo,'' the massive crowd chanted as
Milosevic and other speakers denounced the alleged nationalism of
Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority and indirectly attacked other
opponents of the Serbian leader.
   In Pristina, Kosovo's capital, tens of thousands of ethnic
Albanians defied appeals from provincial and national Communist
Party leaders to stay home and roamed city streets, shaking their
fists and chanting anti-Milosevic slogans.
   It was the third straight day of street protest in Pristina,
where trouble began Thursday after pressure from Milosevic forced
the resignation of two of the most popular Communist leaders from
Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority.
   One of the ousted leaders, Azem Vlasi, met at least 20,000
students and workers gathered in a Pristina sports hall and begged
them to return home.
   ``Without Azem, there will be no unity,'' chanted the crowds in
the streets outside. ``We too are the people,'' the protesters
shouted, challenging Milosevic's claim that rallies backing his
demands represent the popular will.
   The apparently organized shows of strength by both sides in the
long-simmering dispute over Kosovo culminated in today's Belgrade
rally, the biggest of dozens orchestrated by Milosevic supporters in
recent months.
   ``No power can halt'' the fight for Kosovo started by the
rallies, Milosevic told the cheering Belgrade crowd.
   ``We enter this battle as we enter all battles _ to win,'' he
proclaimed.
   Organizers claimed 1.3 million people converged on Belgrade for
the rally, which Milosevic called the biggest gathering in the city
since hundreds of thousands of people celebrated liberation from the
Nazis on Oct. 20, 1944.
   Belgrade television put the figure at 800,000, while foreign
observers said the number was considerably lower. Police had no
immediate estimate.
   Milosevic, who told foreign reporters today's rally was ``very
important,'' is pressing for changes in the 1974 constitution which
gave Kosovo broad autonomy. The Serbian leader argues this is the
only way to protect Kosovo's Serb and Montenegrin minority against
alleged harassment from the ethnic Albanian majority in the
province, which borders communist Albania and was the heart of
Serbia's medieval empire.
   Serbs also frequently claim that the ethnic Albanians want to
unite with neighboring communist Albania.
   Chants of ``Slobo, Slobo, Slobodo,'' resounded through the crowd
on the banks of the Sava River as Milosevic appeared at the rally on
a giant tribune flanked by Serbian and Yugoslav national flags and
topped with a portrait of communist Yugoslavia's founding father,
Josip Broz Tito.
   ``Slobo'' is short for Milosevic's first name, while ``Slobodo''
means freedom in Serbian.
   To his supporters, Milosevic is ``the second Tito,'' the strong
leader Yugoslavia needs to guide it out of political and economic
crisis.
   Critics fear Milosevic's drive for more Serbian control over
Kosovo will lead to an increased Serbian dominance in the country,
which is a loose federation of six republics and Serbia's provinces
of Kosovo and Vojvodina.
   In a 15-minute speech that ended the 90-minute rally, Milosevic
invoked powerful memories of Serbia's victorious struggles against
the Germans in World War I and World War II and compared these to
the current struggle for Kosovo.
   But he also appealed twice to Kosovo's ethnic Albanians ``to
unite against evil and hatred, against chauvinists ... who shame
their people'' and to share in the ``peaceful dream'' of a Kosovo
where children from the ethnic Albanian majority and Serb minority
could play together in peace.
   Milosevic also made a strong pitch for a series of economic and
political reforms the Communist Party leadership has designed to try
to solve an unprecedented economic crisis that has helped fuel the
recent ethnic unrest.
   Columns of well-marshaled demonstrators waving flags, chanting
slogans and singing nationalist Serbian songs moved through
Belgrade's city center from the early morning. At least 50,000 were
brought in on free trains and buses.
   Free food and warm drinks were handed out to participants, who
also had free kindergartens available for their children.
   There also were strong if indirect attacks on the liberal
northern republic of Slovenia, whose Communist Party leaders have
accused Milosevic of using neo-Stalinist tactics to whip up popular
support for his policies.
   People who denounce the armed forces or Serbian policies are
``anti-Yugoslav,'' said Belgrade Communist Party leader Rados
Smilkovic in a broadside at the Slovene leadership.
   There has been vocal criticism of the army in Slovenia.
</TEXT>
