<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 0856EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pakistan-Election     11-19 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Election,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistanis Vote For Provincial Assemblies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistanis voted today for four
provincial assemblies, three days after Benazir Bhutto's party
captured the largest bloc of seats in National Assembly balloting.
   Humayun Khan, Election Commission spokesman, said after the polls
closed today that turnout appeared to be slightly under 50 percent.
   ``It was very peaceful. There were some scuffles at one or two
places but that's almost to be expected,'' he said.
   The police and military had prepared for possible violence but
the second phase of Pakistan's first free elections in 11 years
passed with no serious incidents. At stake were 460 Moslem and 23
non-Moslem seats in the provinces of Punjab, Sind, Baluchistan and
North West Frontier.
   The provincial assemblies are similar to state legislatures in
America. The National Assembly, elected Wednesday, is the lower
house of Parliament.
   In Pakistan, where the presidential election is indirect, the
Senate, or upper house of Parliament; the National Assembly; and the
four provincial assemblies form the electoral college to elect the
president. The provinces also provide the power base for the federal
government in Islamabad.
   Results of today's elections will not be known until Sunday but
observers predicted local and ethnic parties would emerge strongly.
   Ms. Bhutto's left-leaning Pakistan People's Party is strongest in
the populous provinces of Sind and Punjab, but parties such as the
socialist People's National Party have their biggest following in
arid Baluchistan and the rugged frontier province. Ms. Bhutto will
be seeking a further validation of her party's nationwide popularity
in the provincial voting.
   In the National Assembly vote on Wednesday, Ms. Bhutto's party
won 92 of 215 seats at stake.
   Her conservative rivals, the Islamic Democratic Alliance, polled
55 seats, the last being awarded late Friday after officials
resolved a dispute in the Chakwal district of Punjab. The remaining
68 seats went to independents, minor parties and non-Moslem
candidates.
   Ms. Bhutto won a plurality but not a majority in the new
legislature. However, she claimed Friday she had been assured enough
support from other elected candidates to command more than half the
seats of the assembly.
   She refused to divulge numbers or give details of her support,
but if correct, Ms. Bhutto could become prime minister.
   The mandate to form a government must come from president Ghulam
Ishaq Khan but he has not indicated when he will act. Under the
constitution, he could wait until the National Assembly is sworn in,
which must occur by Dec. 16.
</TEXT>
