<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd item to CORRECT spelling to Eckstine, sted Eckstein.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singers Smokey Robinson, Billy Eckstine Daryl Hall
and John Oates are leading a parade of stars celebrating the
reopening of the 60-year-old Fox Theater after an $8.1 million
restoration.
   The Count Basie Orchestra also was scheduled to perform tonight
in the 5,100-seat ``temple of amusement,'' as the Fox was called
when it first opened.
   ``I'm amazed that we've taken the Fox this far,'' said Ray
Shepardson, a theater consultant. ``It not only looks like 1928, it
is 1928.''
   The theater was home to a children's dancing school and a nightly
talent revue in its early years.
   During World War II, shows were held at 2 a.m. for night-shift
workers at war plants. Later, Dean Martin and Jerry Lewis performed
six shows a day during a stint at the Fox in 1951. The theater
gradually fell into disrepair, however.
   New owner Mike Ilitch is putting the headquarters for his Little
Caesar International pizza company in a 10-story office building
next to the Fox. The theater and office building are expected to key
a major redevelopment of the downtown area.
</TEXT>
