<1ST_LINE>i i PM-Angola-War     11-19 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola-War,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader Says Tacit Cease-Fire in Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMBA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebel leader Jonas Savimbi says his
anti-Marxist guerrillas and Cuban forces in Angola are observing an
informal cease-fire and conducting negotiations while awaiting the
outcome of regional peace talks.
   Savimbi told reporters at his bush headquarters Friday that a
delegation of his National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola, or UNITA, met Aug. 26 in the Ivory Coast with
representatives of Cuban President Fidel Castro.
   UNITA is backed by the United States and South Africa.
   The purpose of the talks was to turn over two of the 17 Cuban
officers captured by UNITA during fighting against Angola's
Cuban-and Soviet-backed Marxist government. But Savimbi said the
delegates also arranged ``a tacit understanding that if we don't
harass them, they won't attack us.''
   Later, in an interview with The Associated Press, Savimbi said he
has agreed to a U.S. proposal to provide food to civilians on the
government side of the Angolan civil war. The guerrilla leader said
his only condition is that Americans should be allowed into northern
Angola to make sure the food goers to civilians and not government
soldiers.
   Savimbi said President-elect George Bush had promised him before
and after the U.S. election that American support to UNITA would
continue until the Soviets stop supplying the government and 50,000
Cuban troops leave the nation. At the news conference, Savimbi said
Castro has asked for a further meeting at which a system of
communications will be discussed so that UNITA guerrillas know if
Cubans are part of a government convoy and can avoid attacking them.
   He said Cubans have not attacked his forces ``for some time'' but
claimed Soviet personnel had engaged in fighting.
   ``The Cubans are staying behind. They are not playing a major
role. They are not visible,'' said Savimbi.
   He also said South African President P.W. Botha had invited him
to a meeting in Pretoria on Wednesday to discuss a U.S.-mediated
peace plan designed to get Cuban troops out of Angola and end South
African rule over South-West Africa, also known as Namibia. On
Friday, the Angolan and Cuban governments formally approved the
tentative peace accord. South Africa's Cabinet is expected to
discuss the matter in a few days.
   Negotiators from Angola, Cuba and South Africa, under U.S.
mediation, agreed Tuesday in Geneva to submit a timetable to their
respective governments for the redeployment to the north of the
country and ultimate pullout of the Cuban troops. South Africa says
agreement on a Cuban withdrawal is a precondition for allowing
independence for Namibia.
   Savimbi said he did not care how long the Cubans take to leave,
as long as they all go. He is confident that without Cuban support
the Marxist Angolan forces would have no choice but to negotiate
with him on a reconciliation government leading to free elections,
which he believes he would win.
   Savimbi said that, unlike anti-government rebels in Afghanistan
who have attacked the retreating Soviet army, his rebels would leave
departing Cuban troops alone. ``The best victory is to allow the
enemy to go,'' Savimbi said.
   UNITA has been fighting for a share of power since shortly after
Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
   The group's intelligence chief, Gen. Peregrino Wambo, said that
in the past month 48 UNITA soldiers had died, while the Angolan
government has lost 531 men and the Cubans 12.
</TEXT>
