<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0483,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Strike Paralyzes Occupied Territories, 12 Wounded</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 12 injured, DELETES erroneous
description of Egyptian reaction to PLO declaration of statehood. No
pickup.
^By ALLYN FISHER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and wounded 12
Palestinians in the occupied territories today, hospital officials
said, during a general strike ordered by the underground leaders of
the uprising.
   Soldiers and stone-throwing Palestinians clashed after troops
raided villages near the West Bank's largest city of Nablus, Arab
news reports said.
   Five Palestinians, including a 65-year-old woman, received
gunshot wounds during a three-hour clash with troops in the Karawa
Beni Hassan village, an official at Al Ittihad hospital in Nablus
said.
   A 20-year-old Palestinian was seriously wounded in the chest in
the nearby Beit Furik village and six other Palestinians also were
shot in separate clashes in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, hospital
officials said.
   In Nablus, soldiers fired live ammunition and tear gas to
disperse protesters, an Arab reporter said. There were no reported
injuries.
   The army said curfews were imposed on five refugee camps in Gaza
and that entry and exit from the Nablus area was being restricted.
Reports of Palestinian casualties were being checked, the army said.
   Businesses were shuttered and public transportation halted in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip during the strike called by the pro-PLO
United National Leadership of the Uprising, witnesses said.
   The strike was also endorsed by Moslem fundamentalists of the
Hamas, or Zeal, Movement to commemorate the slaying of Palestinian
resistance leader Sheikh Ezzedine Al Kassem 53 years ago by British
rulers.
   Since the Palestinian uprising began Dec. 8, 313 Palestinians and
11 Israelis have died. More than 7,000 Palestinians also have been
wounded.
</TEXT>
