<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 1007EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Baltics 3rdLd-Writethru a0455 11-19 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Baltics, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0455,0799</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Commission Criticizes Estonian Declaration</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with commission criticizing Estonia. No
pickup.
^By ANN IMSE</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet parliamentary commission today said
Estonia's declaration of sovereignty runs counter to the
constitution in a ruling that could set the stage for a Kremlin
annulment of the Baltic republic's action.
   In Lithuania, another Soviet republic on the Baltic coast,
activists seeking more autonomy met to decide how to react to a
decision by local lawmakers not to directly challenge Moscow's
control, one activist said.
   In an apparent Kremlin effort to reassure the country's 15
constituent republics, the Council of Ministers met with their
representatives on economic power-sharing, official Radio Moscow
reported today.
   In India, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev said this week's
challenge to Kremlin authority by Estonia was part of the process of
``perestroika,'' the name he has given his campaign for social and
economic reform.
   But a special commission of the Moscow-based Supreme Soviet
parliament that met today to discuss questions of constitutional and
political reform reacted strongly to Estonia's decision, calling it
unconstititional.
   The commission ruled that decisions adopted at Wednesday's
session of Estonia's parliament ``contain a range of provisions that
contradict the norms of the constitution of the U.S.S.R., on which
the Soviet socialist federation is founded,'' the official Tass news
agency said.
   Tass said the commission's conclusions were transmitted to the
Supreme Soviet Presidium, the nation's top collegial executive body
that is headed by Gorbachev, in a move that could presage a striking
down of the Estonian decisions by the national leadership.
   Gorbachev spoke in New Delhi on the second day of a three-day
state visit to India. It was his first public reaction to a surge of
nationalism in Estonia and the two other Baltic republics, Lithuania
and Latvia.
   ``There is a lot of debate on how to approach the problem,'' he
said. ``The country is thinking over what is happening.'' Many
points are considered, ``but not all are constructive,'' Gorbachev
said. ``Some are purely emotional and this has been causing some
negative reactions.''
   But he added, ``What is happening in Estonia is perestroika.''
   The Estonian Parliament on Wednesday passed a declaration of
sovereignty in all but foreign and defense matters and a
constitutional amendment giving its own parliament the right to veto
Soviet laws.
   The Council of Ministers, led by Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov, met
Friday with the officials from the Soviet Union's 15 constituent
republics, Radio Moscow said. ``Speakers said a new economic
machinery must ensure a balanced combination of each republic and of
the nation in general,'' the radio said.
   The council set up a special commission to draw up guidelines for
reforming economic and social management between the central
government and the republics, Radio Moscow said.
   In Latvia on Friday, 50,000 people gathered in the capital, Riga,
to mark the 70th anniversary of pre-Soviet Latvian independence,
said Boris Sokolov of the Democratic Union, a fledgling opposition
party.
   Pravda, the Communist Party daily, today published a letter from
the state prosecutor in Latvia accusing the grass-roots People's
Front and some newspapers in Latvia of of seeking ``nationalist
isolation and separation.''
   Lithuania's parliament on Friday approved a measure making
Lithuanian the official language of the republic and embracing as
its flag that of pre-Soviet, independent Lithuania.
   But the legislators dropped a proposal for limited sovereignty
without a vote after the republic's party leader said Estonia's
declaration violated the Soviet constitution, official media
reported.
   ``People were scandalized'' when parliament dropped the
sovereignty plan without a vote, said one activist who stood on the
square outside all day listening to the live radio broadcast of the
parliament meeting.
   ``The people trusted them, and then they didn't even vote!'' said
the activist, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said the Lithuanian Communist Party chief, Algirdas
Brazauskas, returned from Moscow the night before the meeting and
told deputies they had no reason to confront Moscow when Estonia
already had lost the battle over sovereignty.
   The Soviet Presidium said Thursday that Estonia's claim of veto
power over Soviet laws conflicted with the Soviet constitution and
that the issue would be discussed with Estonian leaders at the next
meeting of the national Presidium. No date was given.
   In recent months, thousands of people in the Baltic republics
have joined grass-roots movements and have tried to use Gorbachev's
programs of social reforms as justification for their demands.
   The three republics were independent after the 1917 Bolshevik
revolution until 1940. They were absorbed by the Soviet Union at
that time under a secret agreement between dictators Josef Stalin of
the Soviet Union and Adolf Hitler of Nazi Germany.
</TEXT>
