<1ST_LINE>r i PM-OPEC 2ndLd-Writethru a0457 11-19 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OPEC, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0457,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Trying To Solve Iran-Iraq Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with comments of Iranian minister,
names of ministers meetings, Indonesian giving talks 50-50 chance.
TRIMS. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC oil ministers today pressed for a
compromise between Iran and Iraq that would allow the ministers to
draw up a new production agreement and raise crude prices.
   Iranian Oil Minister Gholamreza Aghazadeh held secret morning
talks with other ministers of the 13-nation Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries at a luxurious hotel in Vienna.
   He spoke only briefly to reporters as he entered a hotel elevator
to go to his meeting with Nigerian Oil Minister Rilwanu Lukman and
other officials. Lukman also is president of the cartel. Asked if
there were any new developments, Aghazadeh replied, ``Maybe.''
   Aghazadeh and Issam Abdul Raheem al-Chalabi, the oil chief of
rival Iraq, met separately on Friday with other OPEC members to try
to break an impasse that has stalled cartel talks.
   The ministers were scheduled later today to resume formal
discussions in a joint session of two of the cartel's committees.
   On Friday, Aghazadeh told reporters that Iran refuses an Iraqi
demand that the two rival countries be allowed to produce an equal
amount of oil under a new cartel accord. ``I always reject parity,''
he said. The two nations are trying to rebuild after an eight-year
war that ended in August.
   The dispute between Iran and Iraq over oil production has stalled
efforts to draw up new production ceilings that would limit the
recent surge in output and give a lift to sagging oil prices.
   Also taking part in the behind-the-scenes negotiations today were
Oil Ministers Rilwanu Lukman of Nigeria, Julio Cesar Gil of
Venezuela, Hisham Nazer of Saudi Arabia and Ali Khalifa al-Sabah of
Kuwait.
   Indonesian Energy Minister Ginandjar Kartasasmita gave the talks
a 50-50 chance of success.
   The ministers also met for about an hour Thursday evening in a
joint session of two cartel committees, officials said.
   Officials fear that failure to draw up a new accord will send
crude prices into a tailspin if cheating continues to add millions
of barrels of oil a day to an already glutted world market.
   Prices are running $4 or more below the cartel's benchmark of $18
a barrel.
   Analysts estimate Iraq has been producing at least 2.6 million
barrels a day, an amount that could hit 3.7 million barrels next
year with completion of a new pipeline through Saudi Arabia to the
Red Sea. Its quota under a 1986 agreement was 1.5 million barrels a
day
   Saudi Arabia has widened its output to more than 6 million
barrels a day, analysts estimate, well above its daily quota of 4.3
million barrels.
   Iran also is believed to have exceeded its quota of 2.4 million
barrels.
   Iraq in the past has refused to abide by the OPEC quota of 1986,
saying it wanted the same level given Iran. Iran has argued against
granting Iraq an equal share.
   Iraq had said during an OPEC meeting last month in Madrid, Spain,
that it would not accept a ceiling that was a barrel less than
Iran's.
</TEXT>
