<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Egypt-PLO 2ndLd-Writethru   11-19 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-PLO, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0473,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mubarak Expresses Support For Palestinian State</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Middle East News Agency
correcting its report to delete reference to recognition of
Palestinian state. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak today reaffirmed
support for an independent Palestinian state but again stopped short
of fully recognizing the newly proclaimed nation.
   The state-owned Middle East news agency initially quoted Mubarak
as expressing Egypt's ``recognition'' of the Palestinian state.
Later it amended its report, saying the word ``recognition'' was
incorrect and that Mubarak had only declared support for the
establishment of the state.
   ``There was a mistake on the desk here,'' said Adel Amer, an
assistant editor at the agency. He refused to elaborate.
   The Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile,
proclaimed an independent state Tuesday at the end of a meeting in
Algiers, Algeria.
   That afternoon, an Egyptian government statement endorsed but did
not explicitly recognize the Palestinian state. On Thursday, Mubarak
stuck to the support formula but said it was ``stronger than
recognition.''
   At least 31 other nations, mainly Moslem, have recognized the
Palestinian state, and the Soviet Union has recognized the
proclamation while stopping short of full diplomatic recognition.
   In the original remarks reported by the Middle East News Agency,
Mubarak was quoted as saying:
   ``Some countries cast doubts on our position when we said that we
supported the resolutions of the Palestine National Council. They
said that we did not recognize (the Palestinian state). This is our
(Palestinian) cause. We are saying that we supported all the
council's resolutions, and this includes recognition of the
Palestinian state.''
   In its amended version, the news agency twice substituted the
word ``establishment'' for the word ``recognition,'' changing the
meaning of the sentence to an expression of support for the
Palestinian state.
   A few hours after Mubarak spoke today, Foreign Minister Esmat
Abdel-Meguid met with Arab ambassadors in Cairo. In remarks to
reporters afterward, he again characterized Egypt's position on the
Palestinian state as one of support.
   Egypt and Israel signed a peace treaty in 1979, the only one
between an Arab country and the Jewish state.
   Israel has mounted a diplomatic offensive against international
recognition of the Palestinian state. Foreign Minister Shimon Peres
kicked it off Friday in a meeting with 60 diplomats from 42
countries.
   Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin told Israel Television on
Wednesday night that if Egypt recognized the Palestinian state, it
would be ``deviating'' from the 1978 Camp David peace framework
accords concluded with Israel.
   The U.S.-mediated Camp David agreements provided for negotiations
to determine the final status of the Israeli-occupied West Bank and
Gaza, where 1.5 million Palestinians live. Rabin said ``unilateral
action'' would breach that aspect of the accords.
   Mubarak said today that the Palestine National Council took
``very good decisions'' in accepting U.N. Security Council
Resolutions 242 and 338.''
   ``All of these are excellent, advanced steps and should be
exploited in the forward push to settle the Palestinian problem,''
he said.
   Resolution 242 implicitly recognizes Israel's right to live in
peace within secure boundaries. Resolution 338 called for peace
negotiations ``under appropriate auspices'' and was the basis of a
proposal, strongly supported by the Arabs, for an international
conference.
   Mubarak said PLO chief Yasser Arafat would soon arrive in Cairo
for talks.
   ``I shall hear from Yasser Arafat about details of the
Palestinian council's resolutions when he visits Cairo. We also will
discuss future steps,'' Mubarak said. He did not say when the PLO
chairman will arrive.
   The nations to have recognized the Palestinian state are:
Afghanistan, Algeria, Bahrain, Bangladesh, Cuba, Cyprus, Gambia,
India, Indonesia, Iraq, Jordan, Kuwait, Lebanon, Libya, Madagascar,
Malaysia, Mauritania, Morocco, Nicaragua, North and South Yemen,
Qatar, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Senegal, Singapore, Sudan, Tunisia,
Turkey, the United Arab Emirates and Yugoslavia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
