<2ND_LINE>AM-Guitar Death,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Acquitted In Guitar Beating Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who claimed he beat a man to death
with an electric bass guitar in self-defense has been acquitted of
murder and manslaughter charges.
   Mark Douglas Troup Jr., 17, was found innocent Thursday in the
death of Russell ``Rusty'' Nies III, 26, of New Cumberland. Nies
died June 20, two days after the beating in a hallway outside
Troup's apartment.
   The two had fought over the return of property to a sister of
Nies' fiancee. Defense attorney Floyd P. Jones said Nies had
threatened Troup and wanted to fight.
   ``(Troup) did nothing more than you or I would do to defend
ourselves and protect our property,'' Jones said in closing
arguments.
   Marc A. Roberts, assistant district attorney, argued Troup went
beyond self-defense by continuing to strike Nies with the guitar
after he had been knocked down by the initial blow.
   ``Self-defense changed to pure rage and the intent to kill,''
Roberts said.
   Six or seven additional blows by Troup, two of which shattered
the back of the victim's skull, ``were neither necessary nor
reasonable,'' Roberts said.
   Troup still faces unspecified criminal charges as a juvenile.
</TEXT>
