<HEAD>Teen-ager Dies After Tumbling in Giant Clothes Dryer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager found locked inside a
giant commercial clothes dryer died after being tumbled and battered
in the machine for about 10 minutes, police said.
   Rafael Benitez, 18, of Huntington Park died Friday about four
hours after arriving unconscious at Los Angeles County-USC Medical
Center, said Lt. Dan Leili.
   The cause of death was apparently ``blunt force trauma,'' he
said, adding that the death wasn't accidental.
   ``He was trapped inside. It had to be latched from the outside.
It is being investigated as an attempted murder,'' Leili said.
   The unconscious youth was found inside the 10-foot-tall
front-loading dryer by a fellow employee at American Textile
Conditioner, a commercial dry-cleaning company, investigators said.
   ``The heat was on but they don't think it had anything to do with
the cause of death. He died from being bounced around inside,'' said
Sgt. Carl Heintz.
   Benitez was repeatedly struck in the head by the giant baffles
inside the dryer's circular drum.
