<HEAD>Protest Over Dropping Of Christmas Ceremony Leads To 93 Suspensions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEE'S SUMMIT, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ninety-three high school students have
been suspended for three days after boycotting classes over the
cancellation of an annual Christmas candle-lighting ceremony.
   The local chapter of the National Honor Society organized a
protest Friday to persuade the Lee's Summit Board of Education to
reconsider last week's decision to suspend the holiday program held
since 1956.
   The American Civil Liberties Union had threatened to sue the
school district if the society-sponsored pageant, which depicted the
birth of Jesus, was held during school this year. The ACLU told
school officials the ceremony violated the Constitution's separation
of church and state.
   School board members voted 5-1 to cancel the ceremony after
district lawyers told them a legal challenege would be costly.
   About 2,400 of Lee's Summit High School's 2,600 students attended
a school-approved sit-in at the gymnasium during the first class
period Friday, but 200 to 250 students refused to return to class
when the protest was over less than an hour later.
   The students were told they could return to class for an
unexcused tardy or they would be suspended, school officials said.
Most returned to class, but 93 remained.
   The suspensions will begin Monday and last through Wednesday.
