<HEAD>No Violence Reported In Sri Lanka's Provincial Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with polling ended, no violence
reported. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``Batticaola, 136 miles...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voting proceeded without violence today
in the provincial election in eastern Sri Lanka, where Tamil
guerrillas had threatened to disrupt balloting, officials and
residents reported.
   Lakshman Perera, a deputy election commissioner, said no violent
incidents had been reported. He said about 40 percent of the 600,000
people eligible to vote cast their ballots.
   Indian and Sri Lankan soldiers maintained heavy security around
polling centers to ward off possible attacks by the guerrillas.
   Two Indian soldiers were killed Friday night when Tamil gunmen
attacked four police stations in the east, a Sri Lankan military
spokesman said.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said the attacks were an attempt to disrupt today's elections. The
police stations were manned jointly by Sri Lankan forces and members
of India's peacekeeping force.
   Residents of Batticaloa, the provincial capital, said voter
turnout was poor in the morning but picked up later.
   Batticaloa, 136 miles east of Colombo, is in the heart of an area
that has been a constant flashpoint in the five-year Tamil
separatist war.
   The voters are to elect 35 members to a council joining
multiethnic Eastern Province with overwhelmingly Tamil Northern
Province. Northern Province had no election because factions agreed
last month to apportion the province's 36 seats. All candidates were
unopposed.
   The merged council, which will have limited administrative power,
was offered by the national government as an alternative to Tamil
militants' demand for a separate nation in the region.
   De Silva said election results would not be known until Sunday.
   The largest Tamil guerrilla group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, has rejected the elections, calling them an Indian propaganda
ploy.
   In a telex from their office in London, the Tigers said the two
ex-guerrilla groups in the elections were ``mercenaries of the
government of India'' and ``can only only be described as traitors
who will never be forgiven.''
   The Tigers are fighting Indian peacekeeping troops who were sent
to Sri Lanka in July 1987 to disarm the guerrillas and enforce a
peace accord.
   The most militant Tamils say they need a separate state to
protect their ethnic minority from what they say is discrimination
by the Sinhalese majority.
   Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhists, comprise 75 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people. Tamils make up about 18 percent of the
population.
   Most Tamils are Hindus, but in the Batticaloa area many are
Christians whose ancestors were converted by Western missionaries.
</TEXT>
