<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     11-19 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Says No Agreement On Talks, But More Meetings Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said Saturday
that two days of meetings with government officials failed to
produce agreement on future talks between Communist authorities and
opposition representatives.
   Walesa met Friday and Saturday with Interior Minister Gen.
Czeslaw Kiszczak as part of an effort to set up large-scale talks on
Poland's future, including possible recognition of the Solidarity
trade union federation.
   The two sides agreed to continue contacts with the goal of
bringing their positions closer together, the state-run news agency
PAP announced in a dispatch about the same Walesa made his comments.
   The dispatch was the first government statement on the meetings,
which had been wrapped in secrecy.
   ``We haven't come that much closer. ... We hope for political
decisions because there are none at the moment,'' Walesa told
reporters at Warsaw Central Station before boarding a train back to
Gdansk.
   The Solidarity leader said he was worn out after the meetings
with Kiszczak, the first contacts between Walesa and Kiszczak since
Sept. 16.
   Walesa refused to say where the meetings were held. He said
Archbishop Bronislaw Dabrowksi served as host.
   Others at the meeting were Gdansk Bishop Tadeusz Goclowski; the
Rev. Alojzy Orszulik, a church press spokesman; Tadeusz Mazowiecki,
one of Walesa's closest lay advisers; and alternate Politburo member
Stanislaw Ciosek.
   The two meetings took place in an atmosphere of extreme secrecy,
with Walesa on Friday slipping away from Episcopate headquarters in
Warsaw, avoiding reporters waiting at various exits.
   Government, church, and Solidarity spokesmen refused repeated
requests to confirm the meetings were taking place.
   Kiszczak three weeks ago asked Walesa for a face-to-face meeting
to remove obstacles to long-promised talks with the opposition. He
sent another message to Walesa a week ago, but neither side has made
public the contents.
   The so-called ``round-table'' talks were promised by the
government after Walesa persuaded workers to end a nationwide strike
wave in August. The strikers' main demand was legalization of the
Solidarity trade union federation, which was outlawed in 1982.
   Walesa conferred Friday with advisers and officials of the Roman
Catholic Church before the first meeting with Kiszczak.
   Historian Bronislaw Geremek, a Walesa adviser who met with the
union chief, said the only ``decisive'' issue still blocking future
talks was whether the government would show a ``will to legalize
Solidarity.'' If the government would make a positive sign, he said,
``then it seems the chance for the round-table will return.''
</TEXT>
