<DOCNO> AP881119-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 1158EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SummerWhiteHouses Bjt   11-19 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summer White Houses, Bjt,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tradition Of Retreats Harkens Back To Days Of George Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA PARZIALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If George Bush turns his family
estate on a sea-walled Maine peninsula into the next summer White
House, he will follow a 200-year-old tradition dating back to the
nation's first president.
   Since the days of George Washington, U.S. presidents _ complete
with staffs and sometimes with considerable baggage _ have escaped
the pressures of the presidency and the oppressive heat of a
Washington summer with respites in the countryside, seashore or
mountains.
   ``Advisers always stress that the president get out of the White
House and (away from) the kind of craziness that exists there,''
says Marvin Druker, a political scientist at the University of
Southern Maine in Portland.
   ``They've always been criticized for being out of Washington for
extended periods of time,'' Druker continued, but such trips give
the president a break from the pressures of the job and a chance to
gain a new perspective on problem-solving.
   If tradition is followed, Bush's nine-bedroom family home in this
Maine resort town, population 4,500, is the most likely choice as
the next summer White House. And townsfolk, although changrined
about the potential for traffic jams and disruptions, are eagerly
awaiting the president-elect's arrival. Some speculate he may visit
as soon as Thanksgiving.
   Often such retreats have been presidents' private homes: John F.
Kennedy used his family's compound in Hyannisport, Mass., Lyndon B.
Johnson his sprawling ranch in Johnson City, Texas, and Jimmy Carter
his home in Plains, Ga.
   But Benjamin Harrison found his calm in a 100-room hotel in Cape
May, N.J.
   Most recently, President and Mrs. Reagan have turned on many
weekends to Camp David, the official presidential retreat 70 miles
from Washington in the Catoctin Mountains of Maryland. There the
Reagans have watched old movies and held sing-a-longs of Hollywood
show tunes. Longer vacations have been held at the Reagan's mountain
ranch in Santa Barbara, Calif., where he was known to relax riding
horseback, even clearing brush.
   Richard Nixon found solace and sunshine in San Clemente, Calif.,
and Key Biscayne, Fla., but Gerald Ford preferred a ski resort in
Vail, Colo., during his term in office.
   The practice of going home for vacations began with the nation's
first president.
   George Washington traveled to his Mount Vernon estate from
Philadelphia _ where the capital was then located _ twice a year
during his eight years in office, according to Ann Rauscher, a
spokeswoman for the Mount Vernon Ladies Association, which maintains
the suburban Washington, D.C., home as a museum.
   Thomas Jefferson traveled to Monticello in Charlottesville, Va.,
whenever he could during his four-year term, receiving visitors and
writing a mountain of letters _ 55,000 of which have survived.
   Jefferson ``was a workaholic, wherever he was. So it was a change
of pace, but it was not the kind of R & R we would associate with
many presidential vacations in the modern time,'' Daniel P. Jordan,
director of Monticello, said of Jefferson's trips home.
   Other presidents have been known to work much less while on
vacation.
   In l927, Calvin Coolidge spent from June to September at the
state game lodge in South Dakota's Custer State Park. There,
according to lodge manager David Shetler, Coolidge did nothing to
dispell his reputation as ``the most skilled president at doing
nothing.''
   At the end of his stay Coolidge announced to reporters that he
had decided against running for re-election in l928.
   Many presidents brought paperwork with them when leaving town, or
met with world leaders at their hideways.
   In 1929, Herbert Hoover discussed the Naval Limitation
Disarmament Treaty with British Prime Minister Ramsay MacDonald at
his summer White House at Camp Rapidan, a 164-acre camp in the Blue
Ridge Mountains of Virginia. The treaty was later signed and adopted
as a step toward world peace.
   Hoover donated the camp to the Shenandoah National Park to be
used as a weekend and summer retreat for future presidents.
   But it was a mountain camp 70 miles from Washington that became
the official weekend home for presidents in 1942.
   That year Franklin D. Roosevelt had Camp David built in a heavily
wooded area of Catoctin Mountain in Maryland _ where the elevation
kept the camp cool and its isolated high location provided adequate
security. He called it Shangri-La, from the perfect mountain kingdom
in ``Lost Horizon.''
   A number of historic meetings have been held there, including
Roosevelt's 1943 visit with Great Britain's Prime Minister Winston
Churchill and Dwight Eisenhower's conference with Soviet Premier
Nikita S. Khrushchev in 1959.
   And, in 1978, President Carter hosted peace talks between
President Anwar el-Sadat of Egypt and Prime Minister Menachem Begin
of Israel that resulted in a major agreement, the Camp David Accords.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
