<DOCNO> AP881119-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 1217EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-Policies     11-19 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Policies,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Now Looking To Deliver On His Promises</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Transition-The Uncivil Service, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush will be looking to deliver on his
``kinder and gentler nation'' theme when he moves into the White
House, but economic pressures could force him to put some campaign
promises on the back burner.
   The stock market retreat and the dollar's fall in value since the
Nov. 8 election both testify to the concerns the financial world has
about the president-elect's ability to bring down the $155 billion
annual deficit, especially given his promise not to raise taxes.
   Bush has already decided to keep friend and adviser Nicholas F.
Brady on as secretary of the Treasury, and he told reporters at
week's end that he was concentrating next on filling out the rest of
his economic team.
   By all accounts, the director of the Office of Management and
Budget is almost certain to be Richard Darman, the former assistant
Treasury secretary and right-hand aide to James A. Baker III who has
wide knowledge of the inner workings of the executive branch.
   Although Bush was often accused of running an issueless race for
the presidency, he actually made enough speeches and produced enough
position papers to fill a 347-page book published by the Republican
National Committee in the closing weeks of the campaign.
   While some critics said Bush's ``flexible freeze'' plan to
balance the budget within four years was weak on specifics and built
around rosy economic assumptions, Bush did flesh out a raft of other
promises, from a toddler tax credit costing nearly $2 billion to
doubling the federal budget for prison construction.
   Bush will get an early chance to elaborate on those promises soon
after he takes office on Jan. 20, when he will be called upon to
revise the Reagan administration's fiscal 1990 budget.
   ``Given these nervous Nellies in the world financial markets, I'm
sure the new president will want to turn his attention to some of
these economic issues,'' said Gary Bauer, the former Reagan White
House domestic policy adviser and now president of the Family
Research Council.
   But Bauer predicted that Bush will quickly make his mark felt on
such issues as abortion, parental leave and day care, both through
judicial appointments and by ``framing better alternatives'' to
liberal legislative approaches to social problems.
   Bush opposed a Democratic bill in the 100th Congress that would
have forced employers to provide unpaid leaves to parents of
newborns and sick children. He also offered his $1,000 toddler tax
credit plan as an alternative to a $2.5 billion Democratic plan to
expand federal regulation and support for day care centers.
   Bush, in two of his first speeches last week told literacy
advocates and the National Geographic Society that he intends to
deliver on his promises of being an ``education president'' and a
strong environmentalist.
   Congress has already acted to help him keep some of those
promises by enacting a ban on ocean dumping by 1991 and by allowing
parents to earn tax-free interest on U.S. savings bonds for college
starting in 1990.
   He is certain to have a tough time convincing Democrats in
Congress of the merits of his plan to cut the capital gains tax rate
to 15 percent from 28 percent or 33 percent. Bush has said his as
yet unnamed defense secretary will have some tough decisions to
make, including choosing between the mobile MX and the Midgetman
missiles.
   Bush also is committed to sitting down with the nation's
governors to to discuss the continuing troubles of America's schools.
   He has promised to spend more on the $1.8 billion Head Start
program for disadvantaged pre-school children, and to create a new
$500 million program to reward schools that get good results with
poor children.
   He is pledged to spend at least several hundred million dollars
to expand Medicaid coverage for poor mothers and children.
   Bush has promised to convene a global conference on the
environment within his first year.
   Without making any specific dollar commitments, he has said the
time for study of the acid rain problem is past. He has promised to
send Congress legislation ``to cut millions of tons of sulfur
dioxide emissions by the year 2000, and to significantly reduce
nitrogen oxide emissions as well.''
</TEXT>
