<DOCNO> AP881119-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 1248EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia Bjt   11-19 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia, Bjt,0875</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Violence Undermines Government, But No Solutions In Sight</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violence by right-wing death squads, drug
traffickers and leftist guerrillas is practically out of control in
Colombia, undermining confidence in President Virgilio Barco's
government.
   While Colombians largely blame Barco for the worst violence since
a war between the Liberal and Conservative parties left at least
200,000 dead in the early 1950s, it clearly results from the
cautious approach to social reform by the white minority of about 25
percent that rules this country of 30 million.
   Leftist guerrillas pose the most serious threat and demonstrate
most clearly the growing discontent in the lower classes. Fifteen
years ago, the guerrillas scarcely had 1,000 poorly equipped
combatants. Today they number an estimated 10,000.
   The rebels are believed to have thousands of peasant sympathizers
who aid them. They also have mortars, anti-tank rockets,
shoulder-fired ground-to-air missiles, machine guns and other
lightweight modern weapons.
   Police reported 489 kidnappings in the last year, 51 percent of
them by leftist guerrillas. Guerrillas this year have attacked 49
towns, blown up oil and gas pipelines 56 times, ambushed two dozen
army patrols and destroyed bridges, electricity towers and other
public works.
   In addition:
   _Right-wing death squads have killed 249 people in 20 massacres
this year.
   _Drug traffickers have killed 26 judges, a justice minister, an
attorney general, two newspaper editors and scores of other people
in the last four years.
   _About 150 members of the country's two rival cocaine families
have been killed this year in a war over control of cocaine
distribution in New York City.
   The rapid growth of the guerrilla movement indicates the lower
class, especially peasants in rural areas, feel there is no
alternative for bettering their lives.
   Still, no one influential in Colombian politics seems to go along
with arguments that much of the violence results from Colombia's
white minority refusing to change the political and economic
structure that keeps Indians and blacks at the bottom.
   _The minimum wage has stood at the equivalent of about $90 a
month for the past two decades. It is not enough for many to afford
education, medical care and basic foods such as eggs, milk, bread
and meat. It is not uncommon for some families to have one meal a
day of soup made with something like turnip greens.
   _There is no room in public schools for tens of thousands of
children, and many poor families do not have the money for books,
materials and uniforms to send their children to school even if
there is room. The wealthy and the middle classes send their
children to private schools.
   _In the last land ownership survey in 1970, the government found
that 4.3 percent of the people owned 68 percent of the land and that
10 percent of the farmers held 80 percent of the land.
   The government of former President Belisario Betancur government
allowed leftist guerrillas to organize a party, the Patriotic Union,
in 1984. But right-wing death squads have killed more than 600
members of the party, including its president.
   Neither Barco nor Betancur, who first proposed peace talks with
guerrillas in 1982, made a serious attempt to wipe out the death
squads.
   On Nov. 11 a death squad in three vehicles rode through the town
of Segovia in northern Colombia for almost an hour, firing
submachine guns and throwing hand grenades. Forty-three people were
killed and more than 30 were wounded.
   Two months ago, Barco offered to pardon all guerrillas who
surrendered and proposed peace talks. However, the plan lacked any
new approach to Colombia's problems and the government said it would
not negotiate changes in the country's political, economic and
social structure.
   The country's six guerrilla groups rejected the offer, calling it
an ultimatum to surrender, and launched an unprecedented wave of
attacks.
   Barco's government has not abandoned hopes for peace talks and
has restrained the army from taking the offensive against the
guerrillas.
   The army has been held back since Betancur first offered peace
talks. A cease-fire negotiated by the Betancur government collapsed,
and Betancur fired a defense minister who refused to accept the
peace initiative.
   The army's disagreement with a negotiated settlement surfaced
again this month when the country's top general, Defense Minister
Rafael Samudio, called for all-out war on the guerrillas.
   Barco fired him within 24 hours.
   A former Liberal Party president, Alfonso Lopez Michelsen, said
last month the 170,000-man military must be increased by 50 percent
to meet the guerrilla threat.
   The country's most influential newspaper, El Tiempo, a Bogota
daily that traditionally supports the Liberal Party, has criticized
Barco's peace initiatives and called for doubling the size of the
army.
   With the government's refusal to negotiate substantial social
changes and with the army gaining support for a military solution,
it appears inevitable Colombia is headed for even more violence.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tom Wells has covered Latin American for nearly
15 years, reporting from Mexico City, Peru and Bolivia. He has been
AP chief of bureau in Colombia for 10 years.
</TEXT>
