<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 1333EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EnvironmentalRefugees     11-19 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Environmental Refugees,334</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EST, Embargo set by source.
^Environmental Refugees May Soon Outnumber Those Displaced by War,
Rebellion</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer+WASHINGTON (AP)et by source.
^Environmental Refugees May Soon Outnumber Those Displaced by War,</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ There are more than 10
million refugees who have been forced to flee their homes because of
environmental disasters or degraded lands and their number may soon
exceed those displaced by war or rebellion, an environmental
research group said Saturday.
   ``Because migration is a last resort _ when conditions become so
poor that life itself is in imminent danger _ the rising number of
environmental refugees should be seen as an important indicator of
the extent and severity of worldwide environmental deterioration,''
said the Worldwatch Institute in a report.
   Worldwatch's figures count people displaced as a result of
long-term environmental changes such as the encroachment of deserts
on pastureland in Africa as well as sudden disasters such as the
recent flooding in Bangladesh.
   It estimated that there are about 10 million refugees as a result
of such environmental changes, compared to about 13 million who have
been displaced by wars or rebellions.
   Land degradation takes many forms and may involve erosion,
waterlogging or excessive salt buildup from poor irrigation.
   According to some estimates, as many as 20 million acres of
agricultural land is destroyed each year by either a shortage of
water, causing desertification, or too much water, causing land to
become waterlogged.
   Meanwhile, another report suggested that while the effort will be
expensive much of this land in developing countries could be
restored with the proper techniques and incentives.
   ``Rehabilitating and restoring degraded lands is at least as much
a social, economic and political problem as an ecological one,''
said the report by the World Resources Institute. It cited as
examples land rehabilitation programs in Egypt, India and China
   The report gave no cost estimate for such rehabilitation, but
noted that 10 forestry and watershed rehabilitation projects
recommended by the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization
would cost $1 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881119-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 1350EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada Bjt   11-19 0802</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada, Bjt,0839</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Pact Turns Campaign Into Debate Over Canada's Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the campaign for Monday's election started
seven weeks ago, no one predicted it would become a debate over
Canada's future, its national identity and perhaps its very soul.
   But the question of whether to proceed with the free trade
agreement that would eliminate trade barriers between the United
States and Canada quickly overshadowed other issues and electrified
the race.
   Instead of the prevailing view that Canadian identity was
insecure and fragile, each side found it had a lot to be proud of in
Canada, despite vastly different interpretations.
   The election will decide much more than the 295 seats in the
House of Commons.
   It also will determine if the trade agreement goes into effect
Jan. 1 as scheduled, and it may set a new vision of Canada as a
mature nation.
   Only a majority government for Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's
Progressive Conservative Party assures enforcement of the pact
Mulroney signed with President Reagan on Jan. 2. The agreement has
been approved by the U.S. Congress and still needs Canadian
parliamentary approval to take effect.
   Mulroney says the agreement is crucial to future Canadian
prosperity by assuring access to the larger U.S. market.
   John Turner's Liberal Party and the socialist New Democratic
Party, headed by Ed Broadbent, oppose the deal. They say free trade
would reduce Canada to a junior partner of the United States, its
sovereignty restricted and its basic identity threatened.
   Polls indicate a close race between the Conservatives and the
Liberals, with the New Democrats trailing in third place. But a
victory for either opposition party, or a minority government, would
effectively block the agreement.
   Mulroney led the Conservatives to a landslide victory in 1984 in
the House of Commons. He appeared headed for another easy mandate
when he called the election Oct. 1 and dissolved Parliament.
   The Liberals, long a dominant force in Canadian politics, were
still recovering from their 1984 defeat and divided by internal
tensions over Turner's leadership.
   Broadbent was hoping his personal popularity could spark the New
Democrats to their best showing ever.
   Although opinion was divided on the free trade agreement, polls
initially showed strong support for the Conservatives, whose four
years in office were marked by general prosperity.
   But all that changed in a nationally televised debate between
Turner and Mulroney on Oct. 25.
   The silver-haired Liberal forcefully told Mulroney that the prime
minister had ``sold us out'' with an agreement that would turn
Canada into ``a pale replica of the United States.''
   ``You've been scaremongering,'' Mulroney responded, saying there
was ``not the slightest justification'' for such fears.
   But the debate made the trade issue the focus of the rest of the
campaign.
   Canada and the United States are each other's biggest trading
partners, with about $150 billion worth of goods crossing the border
_ the strongest trade partnership in the world.
   The agreement would phase out all tariffs between the two nations
over a 10-year period, creating a unified North American market
aimed at 245 million Americans and 26 million Canadians.
   Mulroney and other supporters of the agreement argue that it
won't affect Canadian traditions or sovereignty. They say that
without assured access to the U.S. market, Canada risks becoming an
isolated backwater of international trade.
   The prime minister calls the trade deal ``a visionary instrument
of job creation and new wealth, and it is clearly something that is
on the right side of history.''
   He says Canada is a mature and competent nation, able to compete
with the United States without resorting to the high tariffs of
19th-century protectionism.
   But Turner and his supporters say the pact will turn the nation
into a pool of natural resources for the United States and threaten
its social and health-care programs, which are heavily sponsored by
the government.
   The Liberal candidate says the pact threatens the sense of
community and fairness that characterizes Canada, unleashing free
market forces and unchecked competition.
   Referring to the privatized American system of health care, the
Liberal candidate told his supporters that ``when you walk into a
Canadian hospital, they don't check your credit card before they
check your pulse.''
   In the past weeks, a cottage industry of publications has sprung
up for and against almost every aspect of the agreement. In
addition, lobby groups have promoted extensive campaigns to support
or oppose the deal.
   Last-minute commercials from the Conservatives portray Turner as
an opportunist who jumped on the free trade issue to save his own
political future without regard to the country.
   Commercials sponsored by the Liberals show Mulroney saluting the
United States.
   Turner maintains that he is not anti-American or against free
trade but that the agreement is simply ``a bad deal.''
</TEXT>
