<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Polls     11-19 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Polls,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gallup Shows Conservatives Back on Top</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Canada, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Progressive Conservative Party is back in the
lead and could win the parliamentary majority needed for the free
trade agreement with the United States to proceed, according to a
Gallup Poll published Saturday.
   The poll showed Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's Conservatives
with 40 percent, the Liberal Party led by John Turner with 35
percent and the socialist New Democratic Party led by Ed Broadbent
with 22 percent.
   It said such an outcome in Monday's election could translate into
162 seats for the Conservatives in the newly expanded, 295-seat
House of Commons, 14 more than needed for a majority.
   The poll published by the Toronto Star said the Liberals would
have 97 seats and the New Democrats 36.
   Both opposition parties oppose the agreement signed by Mulroney
and President Reagan in January. It still needs Canadian
parliamentary approval to take effect Jan. 1 as scheduled. It would
phase out all tariffs between Canada and the United States over a
10-year period.
   The Gallup Poll was based on 2,097 personal interviews and 1,970
telephone interviews between Monday and Thursday. It had a margin of
error of 3 percent.
   Another poll published Saturday, by Angus Reid of Winnipeg,
Manitoba, found similar results. It placed the Conservatives ahead
with 41 percent of decided voters, 33 percent for the Liberals and
23 percent for the New Democrats.
   Reid, one of the most widely published pollsters in Canada, said
it was inconclusive whether the popular vote would result in a
Conservative majority or minority government.
   A Gallup Poll published Monday found the Conservatives and
Liberals tied with 35 percent each and the New Democrats in third
with 26 percent.
   The last poll by the Environics Research Group firm published in
the Globe and Mail newspaper on Nov. 10 found 37 percent for the
Liberals, 35 percent for the Conservatives and 24 percent for the
New Democrats.
</TEXT>
