<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SupernaturalThieves     11-19 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Supernatural Thieves,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Charged With Theft Through Fortunetelling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two women have been accused of using
claims of supernatural powers and ceremonies with live chickens to
extort thousands of dollars from superstitious customers.
   Gardenia Ann Ephraim, 42, and her daughter, Mary Ann Ephraim, 22,
both of West Hartford, were arrested late Thursday at a rented house
occupied by 14 people.
   The two were arraigned Friday on charges of first-degree larceny
by extortion and fortunetelling and other fraudulent practices. They
were being held in lieu of $100,000 each.
   Their arrests culminated a monthlong investigation into a
complaint by a 37-year-old West Hartford man. The man and his wife
had sought assistance from the women _ whom he knew as ``Helene''
and ``Helena'' _ for help in overcoming his impotence so he and his
wife could have children.
   According to police, the women convinced the man that he and his
wife were possessed by evil. To rid themselves of the evil, the
couple paid $32,000 in cash and goods between March and
mid-November, police said.
   A police affidavit described a series of bizarre spiritual
sessions. On the first visit, the man was given an egg and told to
put it under his mattress to absorb evil from him. Another time, the
two were instructed to bring two live chickens. The wife was then
told to breathe into one chicken's mouth, and the chicken died 20
minutes later. The couple then paid $600 to bury the chicken and the
evil it contained, and an additional $400 to bury the other chicken.
   The man continued to visit the house for months, police said.
   West Hartford police started the investigation after a friend of
the man's mother told a New Britain police detective about the
amount of money involved.
   Lt. Stephen Lovett, of the West Hartford special investigations
division, said the man told investigators that he had introduced the
women to four people he knew who needed spiritual help. Police have
been unable to make contact with the four, but the money involved in
all five cases, according to the man's statements, totals $107,000,
Lovett said.
   Lovett said the two women and the others in the house appeared to
be living well. Police found expensive furniture and furnishings,
videocameras and stereo equipment. Three vehicles parked in back
included a Porsche, he said.
   Police did not know how many other people paid money to the
spiritualists, Lovett said. People who seek their help usually do so
after seeing advertisements in fliers or Portugese- and
Italian-language newspapers.
   Steven F. Meo, a lawyer representing the two women, told the
court they have lived in Connecticut for about five years and each
woman has an arrest record in Connecticut for fortunetelling.
   Police have recovered $1,500 and safety deposit-box keys from six
banks in Connecticut and seven in New York and New Jersey. The banks
have been notified and Lovett said police would seek a court order
to freeze the contents.
   Undercover officers arrested a third woman at the house in March
after paying $40 to have their fortunes read.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
