<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Switzerland-Bomb     11-19 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Switzerland-Bomb,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Bomb Victims Remain Hospitalized In Switzerland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities Saturday were searching for a man
spotted near the scene of a bomb blast that damaged the Geneva
office of the Soviet airline Aeroflot and injured five people,
including two American tourists.
   Four victims remained hospitalized with leg wounds and burns.
   Authorities examined clues in the rubble of the explosion, which
occurred on a busy downtown sidewalk at the start of Friday's
evening rush hour.
   The bomb, hidden in a sidewalk wastebasket, shattered the front
window of the Aeroflot office on the ground floor of a building also
housing two Arab banks. The injured were passers-by.
   Police were looking for an unidentified man in his 20s who was
spotted near the wastebasket before the blast, spokesman Marcel
Vaudroz said. Vaudroz said the intended target of the attack
remained a mystery.
   Police and the Swiss Federal Prosecutor's Office were questioning
the seriousness of a caller to Swiss television Friday who claimed
the attack in the name of a previously unknown Socialist Nationalist
Front. The caller said communists, capitalists and Jews were the
target, the TV station reported.
   Roland Hauenstein, a spokesman for the prosecutor's office, said
the probe was expected to take some time.
   Anne-Florence Dami, a spokeswoman at a Geneva hospital where the
four victims remained, said all were in stable condition.
   They included Helen Mattheis, 22, of Cincinnati, who underwent
surgery to remove shrapnel from her legs.
   The fifth victim, Ms. Mattheis' mother, Eula Bingham, 59, also of
Cincinatti, was treated for ear problems Friday night and released.
   Ms. Bingham, a vice president and dean at the University of
Cincinnati, called the university to say her daughter was recovering
well after the surgery. University officials reported Ms. Bingham
told them she returned to her hotel after the blast but was having
trouble hearing. She was said to be in Geneva to deliver a paper at
a World Health Organization meeting.
   Also still hospitalized were an Italian man, 34, a Frenchwoman,
60, and a Frenchman, 21. Police withheld their identities.
</TEXT>
