<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Poison Pen,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Author of Poison-Pen Letters Sentenced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Leningrad worker who wrote ``threatening and
libelous'' letters to party, government and police officials in the
name of a right-wing organization has been sentenced to 18 months
probation, Tass said Saturday.
   Criminal investigators tracked down Arkady Norinsky after he
mailed letters signed ``Gunmen of the Pamyat Patriotic
Organization'' to Leningrad residents in July and August, the
official news agency said. It said Norinsky admitted writing the
letters.
   Pamyat, or ``Memory'' in Russian, is a private group that blames
Russia's ills on a conspiracy of Jews, Freemasons and foreigners.
Tass said Norinsky denied any links with the group and that he wrote
the letters in an effort to discredit it.
   ``He attributed his actions to a feeling of indignation at the
content of speeches delivered by some Pamyat leaders,'' Tass said.
``He mailed the threats guided by a desire `to condition some
influential people in the city against Pamyat.'''
   Tass gave no examples of the threats contained in the letters.
