<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Dolphins     11-19 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Dolphins,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dolphins Stranded In Cairo Hotel Being Flown To France</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two dolphins stranded in the swimming pool of
a luxury hotel overlooking the Nile for the past year are to be
flown to an aquarium on the French Riviera.
   Leo and Nemo were brought to Cairo from Switzerland to perform
for guests of the Meridien Hotel and were abandoned after their
contract ended May 31. Their Swiss owner, the International Dolphin
Show Co., said it had nowhere to keep the mammals.
   The two dolphins have become lethargic, swimming in endless
circles around the pool, said Edouard Speck, the hotel's general
manager.
   ``We are now concerned with the safety of the animals,'' he said.
``We can't guarantee their safety and well-being in the pool. They
were becoming weak.''
   The two mammals are to be flown Wednesday to the Marine Land
aquarium in Antibes, on the southeast coast of France.
   To prepare them for the trip, the dolphins will be coated with
grease so they can retain their moisture and will be strapped to
hanging mats, Speck said. British veterinarian David Taylor, who is
preparing the animals for the transfer, also has given them vitamins.
   Speck said the hotel plans to sue the International Dolphin Show
Co. to determine who owns the dolphins.
   ``This is not a confiscation,'' he said. ``We will go to court
later to see whom the animals belong to, who should pay their
expenses. I don't think they will return to the owner. He can't take
care of animals.''
   Bruno Lienhardt, owner of the Swiss company, was traveling and
unavailable for comment.
   Speck said he pressed Egypt's Ministry of Agriculture for
permission to transfer the dolphins. The dolphins will remain under
the control of the Egyptian government pending a court decision.
   ``Whenever the Egyptian government wants them back, they will
have to come back,'' he said.
   Leo and Nimo, born respectively in 1979 and 1980, were brought to
the Meridien in November 1987. Their show was opened by President
Hosni Mubarak's wife, Suzanne, and was a big success, especially
during weekly performances for poor children.
   After the summer season began in May, the dolphins remained in
the hotel's main pool on a veranda overlooking the Nile River.
Guests had to use a smaller pool designed for winter use.
   International Dolphin Show paid the dolphins' expenses through
last August. Since then, the hotel has spent about $565 a month for
the mammals' two meals of frozen fish a day and weekly check-ups by
a veterinarian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881119-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 1504EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-DemocratsText     11-19 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Democrats Text,650</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic response to
President Reagan's weekly radio address:
   I'm Jim Sasser, United States Senator from Tennessee. This week
the world's financial markets have registered strong doubts about
America's resolve to deal with the massive budget deficits we've
built up over the past eight years.
   The message from London, from Tokyo, and the other financial
markets is clear: the day of rhetoric and empty phrases is long
past. As a nation, we've got to demonstrate a serious determination
to get our financial house in order.
   That message was reinforced just this past Wednesday when the
Chairman of the Federal Reserve Board offered a Hobson's choice:
either we get on with the business of serious deficit reduction or
else the Federal Reserve Board will ratchet up interest rates and
possibly induce a recession.
   The markets, the Federal Reserve, they're both putting the
president-elect and this Congress on notice. The declining dollar,
the one-hundred dollar drop on Wall Street since election day, the
threat of higher interest rates, those are the clearest possible
indications that we must act and act now.
   The emphasis is very much on our will to work together
cooperatively. As Alan Greenspan, the Chairman of the Federal
Reserve Board, made clear, the world isn't waiting to see what kind
of plan we're going to use to get the deficits down, it's waiting to
see if there is any plan at all.
   We all know it took a financial disaster of immense proportions
to end the political posturing of nearly eight years. Only after the
stock market crash of last October did the president finally agree
to join the Congress at the bargaining table. The resulting
bipartisan agreement reduced the deficit by some seventy-six billion
dollars over two years.
   I know that I speak for many of my colleagues in the Congress
when I say that we want to work with the president-elect towards the
same positive result, but we can't wait for the next financial
disaster before we again take the budget deficit seriously.
   Congress, just like the financial markets and the Federal
Reserve, is anxiously seeking a signal from the incoming
administration that the era of ideological stalemate is over and the
era of realistic deficit reduction has at long last begun.
   Now, let me say this to President-elect Bush: many of us in this
Congress are very experienced lip readers indeed. We don't want new
taxes anymore than you do.
   We stand ready, though, to follow the president's lead so long as
that leadership aims honestly and forthrightly at solving this
country's number one economic problem.
   In my judgment, the president-elect could begin to send the right
signals to the world financial community and the Congress by doing
three simple things:
   First, he ought to give a fair hearing to the National Economic
Commission. It's a distinguished group of experts, established by
the Congress and the Reagan administration, to help reach a national
consensus on the whole deficit problem.
   And second, he should meet, prior to inauguration day, with the
leadership of both houses of the Congress _ a meeting that should
aim at getting to a common ground, the objectives we all share in
bringing the deficits down.
   And finally, he should get the Reagan Administration to submit a
realistic budget to the Congress this January _ not a scorched-earth
budget that does away with needed domestic programs and certainly
not a document that makes a shrill political statement, but it's
dead on arrival in the halls of Congress.
   Those are the kinds of meaningful actions that will command the
confidence of the international financial community. They'll help to
put to rest the rumors of an early conflict between the Congress and
the president-elect. And I think they'll help prepare the way for an
economic program that will set this country on a stable foundation _
a foundation of economic growth and continually improving living
standards for all our people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
