<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GERING, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church members ended a monthlong quest
Saturday to offer their ``lard to the Lord,'' and two ministers said
they may have started a new dieting trend by getting ``slim for
Him.''
   Teams of dieters from Northfield Church in Gering and First
Assembly of God Church in Scottsbluff planned to weigh in Sunday to
see which congregation won a local contest after 30 days of cutting
calories for Christ.
   Both the Rev. Neal Hail of Scottsbluff, who earned the nickname
``Near-Ton Neal,'' and the Rev. ``Bulbous'' Bill Bibb of Gering were
confident their team would emerge victorious.
   ``We accepted the call to be small,'' said Hail, who dubbed his
team the ``First Fatties.'' He said his parishioners intend to
continue their diets after the contest in an effort to ``get slim
for Him.''
   Although he does not know yet how many pounds his team has lost,
Hail said he is convinced his squad lost the most weight and will
win the prize of a ``Great American Pig-Out'' hosted by the losing
team. To the losing pastor goes a Porky Pig statue.
   But Bibb said the ``Northfield Porkers'' expect to get the free
meal at First Assembly.
   ``Everybody feels good. Clothes are fitting better, and
everybody's looking good,'' Bibb said. He noted the contest has
garnered national and international attention for both churches.
   ``This has caught on all over the world,'' he said. ``I heard
from a minister in Brussels, Belgium, the other day wanting to know
about it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONESDALE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-six senior boys in high school chef
classes whipped up raccoon Sloppy Joes, snapper soup and squirrel
stroganoff for their teachers at a buffet luncheon.
   ``It was their own idea,'' said home economics teacher Elaine
Wells of her students at Honesdale High School. ``They've been
bringing in game since the beginning of the month.''
   The recipes were chosen from books on preparing wild game and
lunch was served Friday to 20 teachers.
   Class members shot most of the game near their homes in
northeastern Pennsylvania. The empty shotgun shells were combined
with dried leaves to make centerpieces to decorate the tables. The
student chefs worked all week preparing the dozen or so dishes using
ingredients such as turtle, squirrel, rabbit, pheasant, and raccoon.
   ``They've done a super job,'' Wells said. ``All the cleaning, all
the cooking. Nothing tastes gamey at all.''
</TEXT>
