<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Liability     11-19 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Liability,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Bill Giving Federal Workers Liability Immunity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed legislation Saturday
that is intended to restore federal employees' immunity from being
sued for personal liability because of their actions on the job.
   The bill does not apply to lawsuits seeking damages from
government workers for alleged violations of constitutional rights.
   For many years, most federal employees were protected from
personal liability, or common law torts, under various court
decisions recognizing that immunity was necessary for them to
perform their duties.
   A Supreme Court decision last January had the effect of narrowing
that immunity, which would be restored under the bill that Reagan
signed Saturday.
   The bill provides that the exclusive remedy for personal
liability lawsuits would be legal action against the federal
government under the Federal Tort Claims Act.
   The bill, which passed Congress by voice votes of the House and
Senate, precludes all other civil actions for money damages based on
a federal employee's alleged negligent act.
</TEXT>
