<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 1526EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     11-19 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sri Lankans Defy Threats Of Violence To Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATTICALOA, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 240,000 people defied a
boycott called by the powerful Tamil guerrilla group and voted
Saturday in the Eastern Province to choose members to a local
administrative council.
   Indian soldiers provided heavy security around the polling
centers to prevent attacks by the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam,
the Tamil militia that threatened to disrupt the voting.
   There were no reports of violence during the voting but a Sri
Lankan military official said two Indian soldiers were killed Friday
when Tamil gunmen attacked four police stations in the region.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said the attacks were an attempt to disrupt Saturday's elections.
   Deputy Election Commissioner Lakshman Perera said an estimated 40
percent of the 600,000 voters in the region cast their ballots. The
polls are for 35 seats on a council joining the multi-ethnic Eastern
Province with the predominantly-Tamil Northern Province.
   The 36 seats in the north were won unopposed by two Tamil groups
that supported an India-sponsored peace accord aimed at ending the
5-year-old war for an independent Tamil homeland.
   At least 8,500 people have been killed in the separatist war.
   The accord, signed in July 1987, provided for the setting up of
semi-autonomous provincial councils to appease the Tamil demand for
self-rule. But the Liberation Tigers, the largest and most powerful
Tamil militia, rejected the plan, saying it fell below expectations.
   The polls Saturday were being contested by the two Tamil groups,
the Eelam People's Revolutionary Liberation Front and the Eelam
National Democratic Liberation Front, as well as the governing
United National Party and the Sri Lanka Moslem Congress. Results
were not expected until Sunday.
   The Liberation Tigers denounced the Tamil groups participating in
the polls as traitors and said the elections were an Indian
propaganda ploy.
   The Tigers are fighting Indian peacekeeping troops who were sent
to Sri Lanka to disarm the guerrillas and enforce the peace accord.
   India got involved in the ethnic conflict because of the
sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils to the rebel cause.
   The Tigers say they need a separate homeland to protect their
minority community from what they claim is discrimination by the
majority Sinhalese.
   Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhists, comprise 75 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people. The mainly Hindu Tamils make up about 18
percent of the population.
</TEXT>
