<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola     11-19 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cubans, Rebels Maintain Informal Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMBA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-Marxist guerrillas and Cuban forces in
Angola are holding peace talks and have informally agreed not to
attack each other while they await results of a regional peace plan,
rebel leader Jonas Savimbi said.
   Savimbi, head of the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola, or UNITA, told reporters at his bush headquarters Friday his
group met representatives of Cuban President Fidel Castro on Aug. 26.
   At the meeting, which was called to turn over two of 17 Cuban
officers captured by UNITA during fighting with Angola's Cuban- and
Soviet-backed government, Savimbi said delegates arranged ``a tacit
understanding that if we don't harass them, they won't attack us.''
   Savimbi said Castro asked for another meeting to discuss a system
of communications by which the U.S.- and South African-backed UNITA
will know if Cubans are part of a government convoy and can avoid
attacking them.
   He said Cubans have not attacked his forces ``for some time'' but
claimed Soviet personnel had engaged in fighting.
   ``The Cubans are staying behind. They are not playing a major
role. They are not visible,'' Savimbi said.
   Later, in an interview with The Associated Press, Savimbi said he
has agreed to a U.S. proposal to provide food to civilians on the
government side of the Angolan civil war. He said his only condition
was that Americans be allowed into northern Angola to make sure the
food goes to civilians and not government soldiers.
   The guerrilla leader said President-elect George Bush had
promised him before and after the U.S. election that U.S. support to
UNITA would continue until the Soviets stop supplying the Angolan
government and 50,000 Cuban troops leave the nation.
   At the news conference, Savimbi said South African President P.W.
Botha had invited him to a meeting in Pretoria on Wednesday to
discuss a U.S.-mediated peace plan designed to get Cuban troops out
of Angola and end South African rule over South-West Africa, also
known as Namibia.
   On Friday, the Angolan and Cuban governments formally approved
the tentative peace accord. South Africa's Cabinet is expected to
discuss the matter in a few days.
   Negotiators from Angola, Cuba and South Africa, under U.S.
mediation, agreed Tuesday in Geneva to submit a timetable to their
respective governments for the redeployment to the north of the
country and ultimate pullout of the Cuban troops. South Africa says
agreement on a Cuban withdrawal is a precondition for allowing
independence for Namibia.
   Savimbi said he did not care how long the Cubans take to leave,
as long as they all go. He is confident that without Cuban support
the Marxist Angolan forces would have no choice but to negotiate
with him on a reconciliation government leading to free elections,
which he believes he would win.
   The guerrilla leader said that, unlike anti-government rebels in
Afghanistan who have attacked the retreating Soviet army, his rebels
would leave departing Cuban troops alone. ``The best victory is to
allow the enemy to go,'' he said.
   UNITA has been fighting for a share of power since shortly after
Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
   The group's intelligence chief, Gen. Peregrino Wambo, said that
in the past month 48 UNITA soldiers had died, while the Angolan
government has lost 531 men and the Cubans 12.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
