<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Romania-Hungary     11-19 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Romania-Hungary,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Romania Expels Hungarian Diplomat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania on Saturday gave a high-ranking
Hungarian diplomat three days to leave the country for what it said
were ``anti-Romanian, anti-socialist and provocative actions.''
   The Hungarian Foreign Ministry said in a statement that Karoly
Gyorfi, a commercial counselor at the Hungarian Embassy in
Bucharest, had been detained for six hours by Romanian police and
accused of distributing ``inciting leaflets.''
   It did not specify what was contained in the leaflets.
   ``Considering the anti-Romanian, anti-socialist and provocative
actions of the Hungarian diplomat ... Romania communicated to
(Hungary) ... that Karoly Gyorfi was declared persona non grata and
he had to leave Romania's territory within three days,'' the
Romanian Foreign Ministry said in a statement carried by the
official Romanian news agency Agerpres.
   The Ministry said Gyorfi's ``very grave actions (were)
incompatible with the diplomatic status.'' It did not elaborate.
   The Hungarian Foreign Ministry said the Romanian accusations were
``completely unfounded'' and charged Bucharest with ``a serious
provocation.''
   The expulsion likely was to aggravate tense relations between the
neigboring communist countries.
   Last summer, Romania closed the Hungarian consulate in the city
of Cluj-Napoca after demonstrations in the Hungarian capital of
Budapest by about 50,000 people protesting a Romanian plan to raze
thousands of predominantly Hungarian villages in Romania.
   Hungarians have repeatedly expressed concern for the welfare of
the 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians in Romania, who they claim suffer
discrimination.
</TEXT>
