<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Missile     11-19 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Missile,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missile Strikes Plane Carrying Sudan's Military Hierarchy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surface-to-air missile hit a plane
carrying the defense minister and several senior army commanders,
but the aircraft landed safely, an official statement said Saturday.
   The incident occurred Thursday just after the Hercules C-130 took
off from Wau in southern Sudan's Bahr el-Ghazal region, said the
statement released by the Sudanese Armed Forces Command.
   In addition to Defense Minister Abdul-Maguid Khalil, the plane
carried Gen. Fathi Ahmed Ali, commander-in-chief of the Sudanese
armed forces, and commanders of major military units, the statement
said.
   It said the SAM-7 missile badly damaged the plane's engine and
the control system. The pilot managed to maintain control and landed
the plane without injury or other damage, the statement said.
   The statement did not accuse the rebel Sudan People's Liberation
Army of firing the missile. The missile was of the type used by both
the southern rebels and the Sudanese army.
   Khalil and his officers were reportedly on an inspection tour at
Wau, 630 miles southwest of Khartoum. The town, which has a major
army garrison, has been under siege by the rebels for months and
also has been the scene of civil unrest.
   The incident came a day after an initial cease-fire agreement was
signed in the Ethiopian capital of Addis Ababa between rebel leader
John Garang and a delegation from the second-largest partner in
Sudanese Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi's coalition cabinet.
   The agreement won el-Mahdi's support and that of other political
leaders. It has yet to be officially approved by the entire cabinet.
   Khalil and his companions returned to Khartoum on Saturday in a
plane sent to Wau to pick them up.
</TEXT>
