<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MagazineBanned     11-19 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Magazine Banned,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Germany Bans Soviet Monthly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist East Germany has banned distribution of a
Soviet monthly, saying the popular publication contained articles
that ``distorted history,'' official media said Saturday.
   The Communist Party organ Neues Deutschland said in a terse
announcement that the Postal Ministry had indefinitely suspended
delivery of Sputnik, a periodical that contains selected articles
from the Soviet press and is targeted for readers outside the Soviet
Union.
   Neues Deutschland said the magazine did ``not contribute to
cementing Soviet-East German relations and instead contained
articles that distort history.''
   In recent issues, Sputnik has carried articles containing frank
appraisals of the Stalin era, along with letters and commentaries
critical of government policies.
   East German leaders have resisted Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's policies of glasnost, or openness, saying they are not
necessary in East Germany.
   Gorbachev enjoys enormous popularity among ordinary East Germans,
who hope the Soviet leader's influence will bring about similar
reforms in their own country.
   In recent months, East German authorities have cracked down on
the nation's Lutheran Church press, censoring or banning
publications dealing with human rights issues.
   The Soviet Embassy in East Berlin refused comment on the
suspension of Sputnik.
</TEXT>
