<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Sun-TimesTalks     11-19 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sun-Times Talks,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contract Talks Break Off Between Sun-Times, Newspaper Guild</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contract talks have broken off between the Chicago
Sun-Times and the Chicago Newspaper Guild, and the union said its
members will strike Monday if the newspaper does not offer them a
raise.
   Negotiations broke off Friday. The newspaper plans to continue
publishing if there is a strike. The guild's previous contract with
the Sun-Times expired June 1.
   Negotiators for the newspaper proposed that the next meeting take
place Monday morning, but the union wanted weekend meetings and had
not decided whether to accept, guild spokesman Charles Nicodemus
said Saturday.
   ``Some significant progress had been made during the week, but
the guild refused to meet again Monday,'' said Michael Soll,
Sun-Times spokesman. He said management had told the union several
weeks ago that no talks could be held this weekend because of prior
commitments.
   The union _ which represents 250 Sun-Times reporters, editors,
photographers and support staff _ had not set a specific time for a
strike.
   ``We only said Monday,'' guild spokesman Thomas Gibbons said
Friday. ``We will set the time, probably on Sunday.''
   ``The company is still seeking pay cuts, (night) differential
cuts and eight exemptions'' from union jurisdiction, said Gibbons.
``We are a long way from settlement and there has to be a pay
raise.''
   The newspaper originally asked guild members to take a 15 percent
pay cut, Gibbons said.
   By Friday, he said the Sun-Times was seeking a 3 percent salary
cut for 18 months of a three-year pact, followed by restoration of
current pay levels.
   Management also wanted to trim the differential paid for working
night and early-morning shifts from 10 percent to 6 percent, he said.
   Soll said he was ``not at liberty to discuss any details.''
   He said the company had filed an unfair labor-practice charge
against the guild with the National Labor Relations Board, and said
the allegation was under investigation. The complaint concerned
aspects of the union's conduct last week, said Soll, who would not
elaborate.
   Some guild members were angered by a letter sent out by the
Sun-Times last week, reminding them of the 1985 Tribune strike and
saying that ``many of the Tribune's former employees will never work
there again. We don't want those kinds of problems for the
Sun-Times.''
   Religion writer Daniel Lehmann said the letter was ``an obvious
threat'' of job loss.
   Soll said the letter was intended only to remind employees of the
seriousness of the situation.
</TEXT>
