<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Democrats 1stLd-Writethru a0553 11-19 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0553,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bentsen Urge Kirk To Stay As Democratic Chairman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 2 grafs new to recast lead and reword for transition;
pickup pvs 3rd graf bgng, Kirk said.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen have
joined the chorus of Democratic Party leaders urging Paul G. Kirk
Jr. to serve another term as party chairman, and Kirk on Saturday
disavowed any role in thwarting Jesse Jackson's political ambitions.
   Kirk told reporters that Jackson's potential influence on the
selection of a new party chairman ``will play no role in my
decision'' whether to seek another term, which he said Dukakis and
Bentsen urged him to do.
   Kirk said he told Jackson in a telephone conversation Friday that
he hadn't made up his mind. Jackson responded, ``let's stay in touch
because that will be important whatever you decide,'' Kirk said.
   Kirk disclosed his conversations with Dukakis and Bentsen, the
party's defeated 1988 national ticket, during a meeting of the
Association of State Democratic Chairs.
   The state party leaders were eager to proclaim the party alive
and well after its latest presidential election defeat less than two
weeks ago to Republican George Bush.
   But they also heard a warning from former Arizona Gov. Bruce
Babbitt that they must stop treating campaigns for the White House
like ``an extension of a congressional campaign'' and start offering
a larger vision of the future.
   ``We assume that what elects a senator will elect a president,
that what wins the statehouse will win the White House,'' said
Babbitt, whose bid for the Democratic presidential nomination ended
after the New Hampshire primary.
   He said the Democrats' success in electing members of Congress
and governors ``makes it even harder to swallow that, once again,
the biggest prize, the presidency, has eluded our grasp.''
   He said that voters regard the presidency as ``about the larger
issues of personal leadership and national destiny. ... To become a
presidential party we must have a vision of what America can become
and the credibility to be heard.''
   As an example, he cited a phrase often used by Dukakis.
   ``Good jobs for good wages may be a good slogan, but it is not a
policy, much less a program,'' said Babbitt.
   He said the Democrats must offer voters an economic message of
``growth and renewal _ not just equity and redistribution'' and a
foreign and defense policy that acknowledges that ``in an imperfect
world we must sometimes project and use force.''
   Kirk's term as party chairman expires in February and he had
indicated he had no desire to serve another four years.
   But many party leaders, apparently eager to avoid a potentially
divisive battle for the post, have pleaded with him to stay on.
   Asked if that included the two men on the national ticket, Kirk
said, ``Senator Bentsen did and Governor Dukakis asked me what I was
thinking about, and I told him it was a serious and major decision,
different from the course I had set out on. ... He said I hope you
stay on.''
   Jackson was not among those urging Kirk to seek a another term.
   The pressure on Kirk was perceived as a strategy for blocking
Jackson from increasing his influence within the national party
structure.
   Kirk said that if he decides to seek another term it would only
be ``to try to do a better job'' and not to ``prevent any conflict
or be an obstacle in any other person's way.''
   He said that if any of his backers were trying to block Jackson
``they haven't mentioned it to me.''
   Ron Brown, a Washington lawyer who played a key role in the late
stage of the Jackson presidential campaign, was the only potential
candidate for party chairman who refused to commit himself to
dropping out of the race if Kirk decides to run.
   ``I don't feel obligated to say I'm not going to take another
breath until he decides what to do,'' said Brown, who emphasized
that he and Kirk had worked closely together in the past.
   If Kirk runs for another term, Brown said, ``obviously it makes
it more difficult, obviously it makes it less likely,'' that Brown
would enter the race.
   He said it was ``a very unfair characterization'' to describe him
as Jackson's man in the contest. ``I would suggest the next chairman
of the party had better have a good relationship with Jesse because
he's going to be around for a long time,'' Brown added.
   Party leaders from the Northeastern states backed Kirk's
re-election as ``the mechanic, the generalist, the builder and
spokesperson this party needs,'' said Samuel Shipley, their chairman.
</TEXT>
