<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SantaTrain 1stLd-Writethru a0571 11-19 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Santa Train, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0571,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Santa Claus Special' Delivers Gifts To Appalachian Children</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs `The four-car ...' to CORRECT by deleting
reference to 25 tons of candy and gifts.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ROBRAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Appalachian children scrambled over rocks
and oily railroad crossties Saturday to claim some of the 12 tons of
gifts and candy tossed from a train during the 46th annual run of
the ``Santa Claus Special.''
   ``Christmas begins this way for us every year, no doubt about
it,'' said Lloyd D. Lewis, spokesman for CSX Transportation Co.,
which supplied the train.
   As in past years, Santa Claus was seated on the rear platform,
tossing gifts as the train slowly passed crowds of children along
the route through the coalfields of parts of Kentucky and Virginia
into Tennessee.
   ``I have people tell me they came as a child and now are bringing
their grandchildren,'' said Frank Brogden, who has played Santa for
the past four years. ``It's a great tradition.''
   CSX Transportation and Kingsport, Tenn., business officials put a
trailer-load of presents aboard the train before it pulled out of
Kingsport on Friday afternoon to get into position for the run.
   The four-car train left the Shelbiana train yard in eastern
Kentucky shortly after sunrise, loaded down with donated candy and
gifts, including 3,000 digital watches, 50,000 cassette tapes of
children's stories, 5,000 toy cars, 10,000 comic books and 3,000
Frisbees.
   The Santa train's route takes it from Shelbiana through 30
communities in eastern Kentucky and southwestern Virginia before
arriving in Kingsport, Tenn., for a Christmas parade Saturday
afternoon.
   The train takes 7{ hours to pass through 110 miles of remote
gorges and valleys, rumbling through 32 tunnels on a rail line
normally used by the huge ``unit trains'' that bring coal down from
the mountains.
   ``For 110 miles, there's not a stretch of this railroad where
you're not looking at a kid,'' Lewis said.
   Georgia Farrand of East Carters Valley, Va., brought her grandson
to see the train when it stopped in St. Paul, Va. She said the train
has become an important Christmas tradition for Appalachian
youngsters.
   ``Children get a lot of joy out of it and they really look
forward to it from year to year,'' she said.
   Santa has been bringing the early Christmas presents to
Appalachian children since 1943, when the line between Shelbiana and
Kingsport was part of the Clinchfield Railroad, Lewis said.
   It started that year with a small group of Kingsport Merchants
Bureau members riding on a car at the rear of a regularly scheduled
passenger train from Elkhorn City, Ky., to Kingsport, he said.
   Passenger service was discontinued in 1954 and from then until
1967, Santa and his helpers rode passenger cars attached to freight
trains. Since 1968, Santa Claus has had his own special train, Lewis
said.
   The train makes brief stops in Elkhorn City, Ky.; Freemont, Va.;
Dante Station, Va.; St. Paul, Va.; Dungannon, Va.; Speers Ferry,
Va., and Waycross, Va., before arriving in Kingsport on the
Tennessee-Virginia state line.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
