<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pakistan     11-19 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bhutto Seeks New Gains in Provincial Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Populist leader Benazir Bhutto sought
to add to her victory in a national election with more gains
Saturday in provincial voting.
   Pakistanis voted for 483 seats in the assemblies of Punjab, Sind,
Baluchistan and the Northwest Frontier three days after they gave
Ms. Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party a plurality in the National
Assembly.
   Results of provincial voting were not expected until Sunday.
   The party led by U.S.-educated Ms. Butto, 35, won 92 National
Assembly seats, compared with 55 for her conservative rivals in the
Islamic Democratic Alliance. The remaining 68 seats at stake
Wednesday went to independents, minor parties and non-Moslem
candidates.
   Ms. Bhutto announced Friday she had been assured enough support
from outside her party to command more than half the Assembly seats
and form a government. She would be the first woman to lead an
Islamic country.
   There were very few reports of violence in Saturday's polling,
even though officials had braced for incidents in the nation's first
free elections since 1977.
   ``It was very peaceful. There were some scuffles at one or two
places, but that's almost to be expected,'' said Humayun Khan,
election commission spokesman, at the close of polls Saturday.
   Military strongman Gen. Mohammad Zia ul-Haq led Pakistan for 11
years until Aug. 17, when he died in a plane crash. Zia ousted Ms.
Bhutto's father, former Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, in a
1977 coup. Bhutto was executed in 1979.
   President Ghulam Ishaq Khan must give the mandate for forming a
new government. But he has no deadline and has not said when he will
do so.
</TEXT>
