<HEAD>Police Say Accountant Offered Car as Payment in Wife Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LARGO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An accountant in the middle of a bitter
divorce has been accused of offering his Rolls-Royce as payment for
the murder of his wife during a meeting with a detective posing as a
hired gun.
   David Stephen Leider, 48, of Indian Rocks Beach, was in jail
Saturday under $1 million bond. He was charged Thursday with
solicitation to commit murder.
   ``A payment of $50,000 was discussed,'' the St. Petersburg police
detective said in the arrest warrant. ``As an alternative to such
payment, Leider offered to sell a $100,000 Rolls to (me) for
$25,000.''
   Leider refused to discuss the details and ``preferred to refer to
the situation as `investment advice,''' said the detective, whose
name was withheld because he works undercover.
   Leider has been involved in a divorce dispute with his wife, Dr.
Zena Leider, a Largo proctologist, since March 1987.
