<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-19 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain From Texas To W.Va.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain fell Saturday from Texas across the Mississippi River
into the Ohio Valley, causing some flooding, and snow fell across
the northern Plains and the southern Plains.
   Flash flood watches were issued for parts of northeastern Texas,
the Missouri Bootheel, western and central Kentucky, western
Tennessee, and southwestern into northeastern Arkansas.
   Central Arkansas got the heaviest rain, with up to 9 inches at
Little Rock from Friday evening to Saturday afternoon, and 6 inches
fell in parts of central and northeastern Arkansas.
   The Saline River at Benton, Ark., just southwest of Little Rock,
was 2 feet above flood stage during the morning, a rise of 16 feet
in 24 hours. The river was expected to crest at 8 feet above flood
stage.
   Parts of western Tennessee got 3 to 4 inches of rain during the
night and many small streams and drainage ditches were full or
overflowing. Dyersburg got 2.5 inches.
   Western Kentucky got 3 to 5 inches overnight with 2 to 3 inches
over the central part of the state.
   In southeastern Missouri, Caruthersville got 5.48 inches of rain
overnight, and more than 2 inches fell from West Plains into Cape
Girardeau.
   Locally heavy rain was reported with thunderstorms from
northeastern Texas into parts of central Mississippi, and Avery,
Texas, got 2.51 inches of rain overnight. Thunderstorms produced
afternoon wind gusts to 70 mph near Gilmer, uprooting trees.
   Street flooding was reported near Summit, Miss., in Pike County,
and 2 to 4 inches of rain was measured during the morning at
Jackson, Miss.
   In the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST, 1.85 inches fell at Memphis,
Tenn.; 1.42 inches at Columbus, Miss.; and 1.06 inches at
Charleston, W.Va.
   Snow fell from east-central New Mexico into northwestern
Oklahoma, and a mixture of snow and sleet was reported over parts of
central Kansas. Two inches of snow accumulated at Gage, Okla., with
an inch reported at Albuquerque and Clovis, N.M.
   That snow was expected to move farther out onto the Plains and a
winter storm warning was posted for the Texas Panhandle, with storm
watches out into parts of Oklahoma, Kansas and Missouri.
   Snow also fell across the northern Plains to the Great Lakes,
from the eastern Dakotas into Minnesota and parts of Upper Michigan.
Duluth, Minn., got 2 inches of snow, for a total of 7 inches on the
ground.
   Elsewhere, rain was scattered into the mid Atlantic states, with
sleet icing roads over parts of Maryland.
   Showers invaded the northern Pacific Coast region and snow was
expected in the Cascades of Washington state.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 10
degrees at Fargo, N.D., to 91 at McAllen, Texas. Saturday morning's
official low was 6 degrees below zero at Gallup, N.M.
   For Sunday, heavy snow was forecast across south-central and much
of eastern Kansas into northern Missouri. Rain was forecast from the
middle Mississippi Valley through the Ohio and Tennessee valleys,
the lower Great Lakes and the mid Atlantic region into New England.
Showers and thunderstorms, some possibly severe, were forecast from
the Tennessee Valley into the central Gulf Coast. Widespread showers
were forecast across the Pacific Northwest and along the northern
Pacific Coast.
   Highs in the 20s were predicted over the northern Plains; in the
30s from the northern high Plains through the middle and lower
Missouri Valley and central Kansas into the upper Mississippi Valley
and upper Great Lakes; in the 60s across southern California and the
desert Southwest, except 70s for southwestern Arizona and the Los
Angeles basin; in the 60s and 70s from southern Texas through the
central Gulf Coast region, the Tennessee Valley and the central
Appalachians into the mid Atlantic Coast; in the 80s across the
southern Atlantic Coast and Florida; and in the 40s or 50s across
much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
