<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 1732EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-BillsRdp     11-19 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Bills Rdp,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Half-Dozen Bills from Final Days of 100th Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has signed into law a
half-dozen bills passed in the final days of the 100th Congress
including legislation calling for stiffer penalties against insider
trading and contractors who cheat the government.
   The White House announced the bill signings on Saturday, although
some took place earlier in the week.
   The bills signed by Reagan also concerned benefits to veterans
who are alcoholics, protection of federal workers from liability
lawsuits because of actions taken on the job; and approval of an
unusual land deal involving Florida and Arizona.
   The law on insider trading was designed to counter the wave of
scandal that rocked Wall Street several years ago and shook the
confidence of the nation's investors.
   The measure doubles the maximum criminal penalties for insider
trading from five years in jail to 10 years, and boosts fines from
$500,000 to $2.5 million for a company and from $100,000 to $1
million for an individual.
   It also holds companies liable to fines for the actions of their
employees if the firms ``knowingly or recklessly'' fail to detect
and prevent insider trading.
   Here is a summary of other bills that became law:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Contractor Penalties</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The measure makes major government procurement fraud a federal
crime and imposes tough, new penalties against contractors who have
cheated the government. It is aimed at giving prosecutors new powers
to deal especially with fraud involving Pentagon contracting.
   The Defense Department has estimated that procurement fraud cost
taxpayers $99.1 million in fiscal years 1986 and 1987.
   Under the new law, those convicted of major fraud in government
purchasing could be given prison sentences of up to 10 years and
fined up to $10 million.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Veterans</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The law overrides a Supreme Court decision that had allowed the
Veterans Administration to deny benefits to veterans who were
alcoholics because it considered alcoholism a product of ``willful
misconduct''
   Under the new law, the VA, when considering the granting of
benefits, is compelled to consider chronic alcoholism a disease as
has been generally accepted in the medical community.
   Last April the Supreme Court, denying a claim from two veterans
that they had unlawfully been denied benefits, concluded that the VA
was not compelled to consider chronic alcoholism a disease.
   Reagan also signed legislation providing a 4.1 percent
cost-of-living increase in the compensation paid to nearly 2.2
million veterans with service-connected disabilities, and to about
323,000 surviving spouses and dependents of veterans who died of
service-related causes.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Workers-Liability</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The law restores immunity to federal employees so they cannot be
sued for personal liability because of their actions on the job.
   A Supreme Court decision last January had the effect of narrowing
the immunity for such workers, but the new law restores the
traditional protection for workers which had been established
previously by various court decisions.
   The new law does not apply to lawsuits seeking damages from
government workers for alleged violations of constitutional rights.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Land Swap</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The law clears the way for a complex deal between a Florida man
and the federal government in which some 107,800 acres of Florida
swampland will be traded for a valuable piece of downtown government
property in Phoenix, Ariz.
   The bill authorizes the Interior Department to dispose of the
104-acre tract of Arizona land known as the Phoenix Indian School,
which the Reagan administration wants to close because of declining
enrollments.
   In turn, the government will get the Florida land, which will
provide an added buffer near the Everglades National Park and other
federal and state lands. The government also will receive $34.9
million, which will be used for an educational trust fund for
Arizona Indians.
   The Veterans Administration, the city of Phoenix and the state of
Arizona also will get part of the Phoenix school property to be used
for various purposes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
