<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--MuseumThefts     11-19 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Museum Thefts,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Museum Closes After Second Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of several Sri Lankan masks purchased for
the University of Pennsylvania's archaeology museum in 1893 has been
stolen, prompting school officials to close the museum.
   A mask similar to the missing one was valued recently at $400.
The mask was part of a collection of objects of minor value
displayed so they could be handled by people with visual impairments.
   On Nov. 11, the world's second-largest crystal ball, valued at
$200,000, and a 2,000-year-old bronze statuette, valued at $15,000,
also were stolen.
   Museum Director Robert H. Dyson said Saturday the museum will
reopen Tuesday.
   ``We're just trying to complete the security system,'' he said,
referring to what he said are electronic improvements.
   In August 1981, the museum closed for about three weeks to
implement security measures following three separate thefts of
artifacts.
</TEXT>
