<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 1850EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UtahQuake     11-19 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Utah Quake,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Earthquakes Shake Northern Utah</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two moderate earthquakes rocked northern
Utah from Salt Lake City to the Idaho border on Saturday, causing
minor damage in at least two cities, authorities said.
   The larger quake had a magnitude of 5 on the Richter scale and
occurred about 12:45 p.m. MST. It was followed 20 minutes later by a
temblor of magnitude 4.6. Both were located near the Utah-Idaho
border about three miles west of Bear Lake, said seismologist Sue
Nava of the University of Utah Seismograph Stations.
   Residents in Logan and Ogden reported minor damage, including
cracked windows and loosened masonry.
   Nava said the earthquake was the largest recorded in Utah since
Aug. 14, when a temblor of magnitude 5 was reported.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 5.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 4.5.
</TEXT>
