<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 1852EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GOPGovernors     11-19 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP Governors,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republican Chiefs See More State Authority Under Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POINT CLEAR, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican governors opened a four-day
national conference Saturday predicting an increased role for the
states as President-elect George Bush builds his administration.
   ``He's a real believer in governors,'' said Delaware Gov. Michael
N. Castle, chairman of the National Republican Governors Conference.
``You're going to see a different America.''
   Castle joined several other GOP chief executives for a bayside
news conference at the Grand Hotel resort at Point Clear, where the
conference is being held.
   The weekend agenda was devoted mostly to welcoming receptions and
a tour on Sunday of the U.S.S. Lexington aircraft carrier docked off
Pensacola, Fla., about an hour from this Alabama coastal resort.
   Castle said Republican governors were closely involved with
Bush's campaign in that the vice president had developed close ties
with GOP statehouses.
   ``Bush has probably met with us more in the last four years than
any other public official,'' said Castle.
   He said the new administration's relationship with Republican
chief executives was signaled when Bush scheduled a speech to the
conference Tuesday and dispatched key advisers, including chief of
staff-designate John Sununu, to take part in discussions Monday.
   The list of those planning to attend includes ``almost every
single person who is coming into power in the White House,'' said
Castle.
   Along with Sununu, those taking part in Monday's sessions include
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, incoming Republican National
Chairman Lee Atwater and his predecessor, Frank Fahrenkopf, and
senior campaign adviser Bob Teeter.
   Alabama Gov. Guy Hunt, who in 1986 became the first Republican to
win his state's governorship in more than 100 years, said a
``century of the states'' is now under way.
   Hunt said President Reagan has been ``turning more power and
responsibility to the states'' and local governments are beginning
to ``stop looking to Washington for the answer to all our problems.''
   Castle said the states already have been leading the way in
pursuing innovative social welfare programs and giving new impetus
to education advances.
   ``The real activism has come from the state level,'' he said.
   The conference chairman said the GOP governors will be analyzing
where the party is and what needs to be done in the future. But he
said it is not just a partisan event.
   He said Republican governors such as Thomas Kean of New Jersey
have shown they are leaders who have the well-being of all segments
of society in mind, trying to develop programs ``that are going to
prevent problems from happening.''
</TEXT>
