<HEAD>Bus Overturns; At Least 10 Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with revised injury toll and other details; no
pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NS1, NS2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greyhound bus hit a tree and overturned
Saturday after a car swerved in front of it on rain-slickened
Interstate 65. At least 10 people were injured.
   All 45 passengers were taken to hospitals, said George Gravley,
Greyhound spokesman in Dallas. Ten were admitted, and two were
listed in critical condition.
   A pregnant woman was admitted for observation, but apparently
wasn't injured. The bus driver, Ronald W. Lightsey, 44, of
Louisville, Ky., was treated and released from Metropolitan
Nashville General Hospital.
   ``The accident occurred at 6:50 a.m. in heavy rain, on a wet
road. It happened in a construction area where three lanes merged
into two,'' Gravley said.
   ``A car swerved in front of bus and in order to avoid the car,
the bus swerved off road, went into a culvert, hit a tree and rolled
over onto its left side.''
   The bus originated in Cleveland, and planned stops in Nashville
and Birmingham, Ala., before arriving in Tallahasse, Fla. Other
passengers planned to change buses in Nashville on the way to New
Orleans.
