<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 2000EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ChessOlympiad     11-19 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chess Olympiad,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Defeat England in Chess Olympiad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALONICA, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union, aided by a brilliant
victory from world champion Garri Kasparov, on Saturday defeated
second-seeded England 3-1 in the sixth round of the Chess Olympiad
to retain their solid 2.5-point lead.
   But in the separate women's competition, Hungary kept a half
point ahead of the Soviets with a 3-0 victory over Cuba.
   In the men's Olympiad, the Soviets have 20 points out of a
possible 24. Sweden is second with 17.5 points.
   The Soviets swept into the lead in their duel with England after
just three hours when Kasparov, 25, forced England's Nigel Short to
resign on the 23rd move.
   The speed with which Kasparov, playing white, demolished his
23-year-old opponent, the third-ranked player in the world,
astonished many experts.
   ``It was a kind of quiet annihilation,'' said Greg d'Elia, an
American master who is in Salonica as captain of Lichenstein's team.
   ``First, he trapped Short's king in the center of the board.
Then, with cruel subtlety, Kasparov waited for Short's position to
collapse,'' d' Elia said.
   A further Soviet victory came on board two, when former world
champion Anatoly Karpov won a pawn and squeezed out a victory
against Jonathan Speelman of England.
   This decisive victory over their strongest opposition leaves the
Soviets strongly placed as the 14-round contest nears the half-way
mark. In the last Olympiad, held in 1986 in Dubai, United Arab
Emirates, the Soviets had only amassed 17.5 points by the same stage.
   Sweden moved up to second place by defeating Hungary, the third
seeds, 3-1 following victories from Ferdinand Hellers and Thomas
Ernst.
   East Germany is in third place, while the United States, who won
the bronze medals in the last three competitions, moved up to share
fourth place with Bulgaria.
   Victories from Yasser Seirawan and Larry Christiansen gave the
United States a 3-1 win over Czechoslovakia.
   India scored a 4-0 victory over Greece's ``B'' team to join the
leading group in 11th place.
   A win scores one point, and a draw scores a half point.
   In the women's Olympiad, Hungary and the Soviet Union, who
defeated China 3-0, have opened up a gap over a chasing pack.
   Hungary, whose squad features a remarkable trio of sisters _
including Judit Polgar, the highest ranked 12-year-old in history _
seized the lead when they defeted the Soviets 2-1 in the fifth round.
   That match concluded Saturday morning when Polgar drew her
adjourned game with Soviet Grandmaster Irina Levitina.
   The Olympiad, held in Greece's second most populous city, is a
biennial world team championship featuring teams from 106 countries.
   The 14th and final round is scheduled for November 29. Unfinished
games will be completed Sunday with the seventh round played on
Sunday evening.
</TEXT>
