<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia 2ndLd-Writethru a0573 11-19 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0573,0863</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Thousands Hold Opposition Rallies Over Ethnic Concerns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Kosovo protest dying down,
other details; picks up 7th pvs `Serbia's drive...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PS1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of thousands of flag-waving
Serbs rallied Saturday for greater control over the troubled
province of Kosovo, while their opponents thronged the provincial
capital in a rally of their own.
   Helmeted riot police closed all roads leading into Kosovo's
capital, Pristina, Saturday to keep ethnic Albanians from converging
on the city. Protesters, who numbered at least 20,000, had mostly
dispersed by midnight, said police officers speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The police actions, later reported on Belgrade television,
followed a warning on the state news agency Tanjug that
``extraordinary measures could be taken'' if the crowds in Pristina,
250 miles south of Belgrade, did not disperse.
   It was the third straight day of street protests in Pristina
triggered by the forced resignations of two ethnic Albanian
Communist leaders.
   However, Kosovo's acting party president told reporters later
Saturday the Communist leadership had decided to use ``exclusively
political measures'' to ease the tension and held out the
possibility that the resignations would be reviewed.
   ``Should it be determined that mistakes were committed in
carrying this out, they (the resignations) will be annulled,'' Party
President Remzi Koljgeci told reporters.
   The mostly young crowds had earlier ignored several warnings from
local Communist party leaders to leave. Tanjug and Kosovo's
Communist leadership said the situation worsened ``from hour to
hour.''
   Serbia's Communist Party leader, Slobodan Milosevic, claimed
Saturday's rally in Belgrade was the largest in Yugoslavia's post
World War II history. The crowd chanted in support.
   Serbia's drive for change in Kosovo ``is a process that nobody
will be able to stop any longer by any force,'' Milosevic told the
crowd.
   ``We enter this battle as we enter all battles _ to win,'' he
added, recalling Serbia's defeats of German armies in World War I
and World War II.
   Trouble erupted in Kosovo on Thursday when two ethnic Albanian
Communist leaders, Azem Vlasi and Kacusa Jasari, were forced to
resign under pressure from Milosevic.
   About 15,000 workers and students rallied in a Pristina sports
hall and later joined a swelling crowd of tens of thousands outside
the local Communist Party headquarters.
   ``We have given our word that we shall lay down our lives for
Kosovo!'' cried the fist-shaking, flag-waving masses, contradicting
Milosevic's claims that the province's ethnic Albanian leaders had
no popular support.
   High-level officials from the national Communist Party were
dispatched from Belgrade to the southern region bordering Albania.
   But the crowds demanded a visit from Stipe Suvar, leader of the
national Communist Party. He is widely perceived to oppose
Milosevic's populist methods.
   Tanjug reported local security officials held an emergency
meeting attended by Vlasi.
   Remzi Koljgeci, acting head of Kosovo's Communist Party, said the
situation in Pristina was more complicated than on Friday, when an
estimated 70,000 ethnic Albanians roamed the city for hours.
   The simmering tension between the ethnic Albanian majority in
Kosovo and the province's Serb and Montenegrin minorities erupted in
violence in 1981, when nine people died in clashes between police
and Albanians demanding more independence from Serbia.
   Martial law was then briefly imposed in Kosovo, which is
administratively part of Serbia, the largest of Yugoslavia's six
republics.
   The 1974 constitution granted broad autonomy to Kosovo, an
ancient Serbian heartland where ethnic Albanians now form 90 percent
of the population.
   Milosevic wants the constitution changed to give Serbia more
control over the province's security, educational and judicial
systems.
   He argues this would protect the Slav minority there from alleged
harassment by the ethnic Albanians.
   Saturday's rally in Belgrade, postponed three times out of
apparent fear it would drive ethnic tension out of control, was
billed as the high point of Milosevic's campaign.
   Hailed by his supporters as a strong leader and heir to the late
President Tito, Milosevic is feared by non-Serb Communist leaders
who dislike his populist style and worry his drive for more control
in Kosovo will increase the Serbian say in national affairs.
   Organizers estimated 1.3 million people attended the rally on the
banks of the Sava River. Milosevic asserted it was the biggest
gathering since hundreds of thousands poured onto Belgrade streets
to celebrate liberation from the Nazis in 1944.
   Independent observers gave much lower estimates for the crowds,
who streamed into Belgrade on free buses and trains or on foot.
   Despite some fiery speeches, Saturday's rally was much flatter in
atmosphere than many expected, with the crowd dispersing quickly and
peacefully afterward as heavy rain began falling.
   Milosevic's fighting talk was balanced by two appeals to the
ethnic Albanians to unite with Serbs and work for the ``peaceful
dream'' of the two groups living in harmony in Kosovo.
   Milosevic also called for support of political and economic
reforms outlined by Yugoslavia's Communist leadership to overcome
the economic crisis that has helped fuel ethnic and worker unrest.
</TEXT>
