<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Graves     11-19 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Graves,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weapons Program Manager Douglas Graves Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Douglas E. Graves, who handled development of
several major weapons systems during a 43-year career with Boeing
Co., is dead at age 70.
   Graves, who retired in 1983 as vice president and deputy manager
of strategic planning and acquisitions for Boeing Aerospace, died
Thursday of cancer.
   He was responsible for development of systems that made the
United States a leading exporter of weapons technology _ sales and
deployments sometimes conducted after long, bitter controversies.
   Graves managed development of the air-launched cruise missile,
which can evade radar by skimming the ground; the short-range attack
missile; the airborne warning and control system, which enables
intelligence-gathering from reconnaisance aircraft; the E-4 advanced
airborne command post; and military uses of the 747 jumbo jet.
   He also was assistant program manager for the Minuteman
intercontinental nuclear missile.
   ``He was very effective and very sucessful in helping acquire new
business for Boeing,'' said Bill Jury, a Boeing spokesman. ``Other
people then would follow up and complete the project. He was very
effective in recognizing the needs for new systems.''
   Graves worked on nearly every Boeing airplane program during
World War II and the 1950s. He then worked on the missiles and
Minuteman program.
   A native of Great Falls, Mont., and civil engineering graduate of
the University of Washington, Graves was a licensed aeronautical
engineer and an associate fellow of the American Institute of
Aeronautics and Astronautics.
   Survivors include his widow, a son, a daughter, two sisters, a
brother and five grandchildren. A memorial service is scheduled
Wednesday at St. Stephen's Episcopal Church.
</TEXT>
