<HEAD>Plane Crashes Into Mountain In Fog, Killing Six</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf, `Independence County...' to UPDATE with
identities of victims; picks up final graf, `In the...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY FREEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATESVILLE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine plane slammed into a
mountain and caught fire as the pilot made a second attempt to land
in dense fog and thunderstorms, killing all six people on board,
authorities said Saturday.
   The Beechcraft King Air turboprop was cleared to land at the time
of the crash Friday, and other planes had landed safely earlier in
the evening, said Jimmy Watkins, chairman of the Batesville Airport
Commission.
   ``The weather was about as bad as you can get,'' said Roger
Williams, a dispatcher for the Independence County Sheriff's
Department. ``The officers at the scene said it was raining and so
foggy you couldn't see the ground.''
   The plane ``had made one approach and missed the Batesville
airport and they were attempting a second time,'' Williams said.
   Elsewhere, a single-engine Beechcraft Bonanza apparently lost
power just minutes after taking off from Brookhaven airport on New
York's Long Island and crashed and burned near the runway Friday,
killing all three on board, said Kathleen Bergen, a spokeswoman for
the Federal Aviation Administration.
   In Arkansas, officials initially had said seven people died in
the crash in a densely wooded area about 12 miles west of the
Batesville airport, where visibility was near zero.
   ``When we first went out there, the bodies were intermingled,''
Dale Rust, coordinator of the state Office of Emergency Services,
said Saturday. ``We thought there were seven.''
   The plane had taken off from Orange, Texas, outside Beaumont,
said Wayne Beckmann, duty officer at the FAA's southwest regional
office in Fort Worth.
   Independence County Coroner George Barnett identified the victims
as Marlin Thompson, 62, a lawyer from Orange, Texas; his wife,
Linda; pilot Michael Beaumont, no age or hometown available; Dewey
Cox, 55, no hometown available; Robin Steele, no age available; and
Martha Beaumont. Her relationship to Michael Beaumont and her age
and hometown were unavailable. The Thompsons owned a 10,000-acre
private hunting preserve stocked with exotic animals near Batesville.
   In the Long Island crash, the victims were identified as Bernetha
Stewart, 32, and Alciha Smalls, 19, both of Charleston, S.C., and
the plane's owner, Charles Stuart of Shirley, N.Y., said Officer
Susan Romann of the Suffolk County Police Department.
</TEXT>
