<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti     11-19 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Avril Invites Political Leaders to Commemorate Election-Day
Massacre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Haiti's ruler, Lt. Gen. Prosper
Avril, has invited political leaders to participate in a ceremony
marking the election-day massacre of voters in November 1987, a
radio report said Saturday.
   In an open letter to civic and political leaders, Avril suggested
that all Haitians were responsible for the massacre that ended the
nation's first chance at democratic elections after almost three
decades of rule by the Duvalier family.
   The slaughter has been widely blamed on supporters of the
Duvaliers.
   Avril said ``verbal aggression and physical violence'' led to the
massacre on Nov. 29, when thugs shot and hacked to death at least 34
voters at polling stations, the independent station Radio Haiti
Inter reported.
   ``Once again possessed by the old demons which over the centuries
have caused us grief, the sons of the nation let themselves be
pitted one against the other,'' said the Haitian ruler, who replaced
Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy in a military coup mounted by lower-ranking
soldiers on Sept. 17.
   ``Avril condemns everyone, and in condemning everyone, condemns
no one,'' Sylvio Claude, a frontrunner presidential candidate in the
aborted elections told The Associated Press Saturday.
   ``It is out of the question for us to commemorate the Nov. 29
carnage,'' Claude said. ``The day could be commemorated if the
culprits were arrested and tried.''
   Though the massacre was carried out in daylight by unmasked
gunmen as soldiers watched in trucks without interfering, no one has
been arrested or punished.
   Soldiers who helped bring Avril to power said they are sickened
by acts of state-sponsored violence. Avril has pledged to return
Haiti to democratic rule, but he has announced no timetable for
elections.
   Namphy had ruled since February 1986, when dictator Jean-Claude
Duvalier fled to France.
</TEXT>
