<DATELINE>SMITHTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A construction worker operating a
bulldozer severed a gas main Saturday, causing an explosion that
killed one person, injured 11 others and leveled a vacant store.
   ``The sky seemed to fall on us,'' said Ann Marie Riley, who was
in a car two doors down from the building. ``Debris and glass was
falling like heavy rain.''
   The explosion in this Long Island town shattered windows and sent
debris flying hundreds of feet, witnesses said.
   A construction crew was working in the business district and a
backhoe operator struck the main, said a Suffolk County police
spokeswoman, Officer Susan Romann.
   The driver, realizing what he had done, ran to a shop to call
police, and while he was there the explosion rocked the area. He was
injured by flying glass, police said.
   The construction company had failed to call the Long Island
Lighting Co. to find out the location of the gas line, said utility
spokesman Jerry Mikorenda.
   The dead man was identified as Anibal J. Leiria, 31.
   Four crew members, including the backhoe operator, and seven
bystanders were treated at hospitals for minor injuries, Ms. Romann
said.
   Janet Risener, owner of a gas station across the street from the
vacant store, said she was doing paperwork when her windows blew out
and she saw a big cloud of smoke.
   ``There was wood and concrete up in the air,'' she said, adding
that nearby store and car windows also were shattered.
