<HEAD>Dubcek Meets With Pope</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek, the leader of the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms in Czechoslovakia in 1968, met Saturday with Pope
John Paul II.
   The Vatican did not release details of Dubcek's brief private
talk with the Polish-born pope, saying only that Dubcek had asked to
greet John Paul.
   The meeting took place after Dubcek visited the Sistine Chapel.
   Dubcek, making his first trip abroad in 18 years, went to Italy
last week to receive an honorary degree from the University of
Bologna.
   As Communist Party leader in 1968, he tried to liberalize
Czechoslovakia's political and economic life. The attempt was
crushed by a Soviet-led invasion and he was removed from the party
and assigned to a low-level bureaucratic position.
