<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Nuclear-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0610 11-19 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Nuclear-Reax, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0610,0719</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Governor-Elect Decries Reagan Order On Nuclear Plant Emergency
Planning</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Moves up Gregg's party affiliation from ninth graf to first
graf. Fixes typo in 6th graf ``Seabrook spokesman....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Gov.-elect Judd Gregg on Saturday
denounced a federal order that could speed licensing of the stalled
Seabrook nuclear power plant and suggested that Gov. John Sununu
helped get President Reagan to sign it.
   Sununu, a staunch advocate of the plant who on Thursday was named
President-elect George Bush's chief of staff, denied any involvement
and said through a spokesman he didn't anticipate the order.
   ``The governor was totally taken by surprise by it,'' said
spokesman Jerry Little.
   The executive order, released by the White House on Friday, gives
the Federal Emergency Management Agency broad new powers to carry
out evacuation plans for nuclear power plants that have been unable
to obtain commercial licenses because of state or local governmental
opposition.
   The $5.7 billion Seabrook reactor was completed more than two
years ago but remains unlicensed mainly because Massachusetts
refuses to cooperate in emergency planning for six communities
within 10 miles of the plant.
   Seabrook spokesman Ron Sher said Saturday the executive order may
have come too late to help speed licensing for the plant. He noted
that Seabrook has put together its own emergency response
organization for Massachusetts and that FEMA gave the organization
passing grades during an exercise in June.
   ``We're very far along in the licensing process,'' Sher said.
``I'm not sure (the order) helps us very much. We may not need
help.''
   Nevertheless, the order provoked an outcry from opponents of
Seabrook and the similarly stalled Shoreham reactor in New York,
which are the only two plants facing conditions that would be
covered by the order.
   Gregg, a four-term congressman who replaces Sununu on Jan. 5,
supports Seabrook if federal regulators determine that its
evacuation plans are safe. But after a draft of the executive order
surfaced in June, Gregg and the other three members of New
Hampshire's congressional delegation met with Reagan to tell him
they opposed it.
   ``The decision to sign the FEMA order reflects a change in policy
which is totally inappropriate and a mistake,'' Gregg said Saturday
through spokesman Brian Grip.
   ``It will, as I told the president last summer, create at the
minimum a perception that the process for approving safety
requirements for nuclear power plants has been fundamentally changed
in midstream,'' Gregg said.
   ``This action, which I strongly disagree with, has obviously been
influenced by new pressures in Washington,'' Gregg added. ``The way
in which this order was resurrected and floated through the back
channels of the White House is totally inappropriate, especially in
light of the concerns already expressed by the New Hampshire
congressional delegation.''
   Gregg did not return a message Grip passed along seeking
elaboration on his remarks.
   Through spokesman Little, Sununu said any inference that he was
involved in reviving the order ``is absolutely incorrect.''
   ``I haven't heard or spoken about that issue to anyone in the
last two or three months, and I thought it wasn't going to come to
pass because it was now being considered unnecessary as the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission licensing process is moving along well'' for
Seabrook, Sununu said.
   Sununu also referred to a recent NRC rule change, upheld by a
federal court in September, that says utilities may submit their own
emergency plans for reluctant governments. The rule change presumes
reluctant government officials would follow the utility plans in a
real emergency.
   When the draft of the executive order surfaced, a Washington
source told The Associated Press that Sununu was ``up to his
eyeballs in this thing.'' Sununu has denied originating the idea or
lobbying heavily for it.
   White House spokesman B.J. Cooper, when read Gregg's remarks
Saturday, said the proposed order ``has been under review for
months. It had nothing to do with what you said.''
   Cooper said Sununu ``had discussions with the (White House) staff
several months ago'' on the proposed order, but ``I didn't say he
lobbied heavily.'' Cooper also noted that some congressmen and
senators also had spoken with White House staff members about the
issue.
</TEXT>
