<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 2225EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Strikes     11-19 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Strikes,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazil Government Makes Offer to Oil Strikers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government made a new offer
Saturday to end the national oil industry's worst strike ever as
supplies of gasoline, cooking oil and other petroleum products were
running out, local news reports said.
   The state-owned oil company, Petrobras, made its proposal after
three hours of negotiations with strike leaders in Brasilia on
Saturday.
   The government offered to pay for five of nine days the workers
have been on the nationwide strike on the condition they end it.
   The strikers originally demanded a 354 percent pay increase, and
Petrobras had offered 70 percent. There was no report of what they
had offered in their latest proposal.
   Oil workers, who earn an average of $300 a month, say they have
lost buying power to inflation, now running at an annual rate of
1,000 percent.
   Members of the National Strike Command in Brasilia said in radio
interviews that they would review the government's proposal over the
weekend. Strike leaders were expected to give their response on
Monday.
   Meanwhile, Brazilians scrimped and rationed to extend stocks of
cooking gas and diesel oil, which had fallen to critical levels. The
respected Folha de Sao Paulo newspaper reported Saturday that
supplies could run out by Sunday.
   In the northeast, canisters of cooking gas were being rationed
one to each household. Residents of some cities waited overnight on
lines that ran more than a half-mile each to buy canisters of
cooking gas.
   Petrobras officials announced in radio and television broadcasts
that an emergency supply of 2,200 tons of cooking gas imported from
Argentina arrived in Porto Alegre on Saturday.
   Of Brazil's 10 oil refineries, three were partially operating
Saturday.
   The total production stood at 350,000 barrels a day, down from a
full-capacity level of 1.5 million barrels. The country normally
consumes about 1.1 million barrels daily.
   The strike is among several in Brazil by workers angered by a
sputtering economy under President Jose Sareny.
   On Nov. 9, thousands of striking steelworkers stormed Brazil's
biggest steel mill, the National Steel Company mill in Volta
Redonda, 80 miles northwest of Rio de Janeiro, and hurled rocks and
firebombs at police and soldiers. Two workers were fatally shot and
another was bludgeoned to death, plant officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
