<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon-Kidnap     11-19 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Kidnap,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Local Army Abandons Search for Kidnapped Swiss Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local militiamen leading the search for a
Swiss official of the Red Cross gave up their effort Saturday after
failing to find a trace of the kidnap victim, their leader said.
   The local army said it scoured the area in and around this
southern port city after 32-year-old Peter Winkler was grabbed by
gunmen here Thursday.
   ``We have searched the whole Sidon region for Mr. Winkler despite
heavy rains and bad weather conditions, but we couldn't find any
clue to his whereabouts,'' said Abu Yahya, an official of the
Popular Nasserite Organization, a Moslem leftist group.
   ``Our security system will remain interested in his case, but the
major search campaign is over,'' he said.
   No group has claimed responsibility for kidnapping Winkler, who
heads the Sidon office of the International Committee of the Red
Cross.
   Officials of the Moslem militia and police believe Winkler was
kidnapped for a possible trade-off with Hussein Hariri, a
22-year-old Lebanese hijacker jailed in Geneva. Hariri, a Shiite
Moslem member of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah group, hijacked an Air
Afrique jetliner and forced it to land in Geneva on July 24, 1987.
He was arrested after killing a French passenger.
   In addition to Winkler, 14 foreigners are held hostage in Lebanon
by what are believed to be mainly pro-Iranian Shiite factions. Nine
Americans are among the missing. The longest held foreign hostage is
Terry A. Anderson, 41, chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
