<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bomb-Animals     11-19 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bomb-Animals,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jailed Animal Rights Activist Says She Didn't Mean To Kill Anyone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A animal rights activist accused of
planting a bomb outside a company that demonstrates surgical tools
on dogs and then kills them says she only wanted to scare the
company's chairman.
   ``It would have been purposeless to kill him,'' Fran Trutt was
quoted as saying in an interview published in The Advocate of
Stamford on Sunday. ``But to scare him at this time might have
affected some change, as there are surgical supply companies that
are not torturing dogs or other animals in any way shape or form.
And their products are working just as well for humans.''
   Trutt, 33, faces attempted murder charges for allegedly planting
a radio-controlled pipe bomb outside U.S. Surgical's headquarters on
Nov. 11. Police said the bomb was found near a parking space used by
the company's chairman, Leon Hirsch.
   U.S. Surgical, a company founded by Hirsch 24 years ago, is the
nation's largest supplier of surgical staplers. Company officials
teach doctors how to use the devices in instructional sessions
involving between 700 and 900 dogs each year. Company officials said
stray dogs previously destined to be put to death are used. The dogs
are anesthetized before they are operated on and are destroyed
before they awaken.
   In the interview from the Connecticut Correctional Institution at
Niantic, Trutt also said she was acting alone and that she did not
make the bomb.
   She claimed, however, that her actions are being hailed by animal
rights activists.
   ``I am not the only who feels this way,'' she said. ``Others are
willing to take action to affect a change so that this live torture
will stop.''
   Some animal rights groups, including one that had petitioned
state health authorities to stop the experimentation at U.S.
Surgical, have disassociated themselves with Trutt and emphasized
that they oppose violence.
   Trutt, who lives in the Queens section of New York City, is being
held on $500,000 bond on charges of attempted murder, possession of
explosives and manufacturing bombs. A second bond hearing is
scheduled for Nov. 29 in Stamford.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
