<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 2315EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TropicalWeather     11-19 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tropical Weather,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tropical Depression Muddles Across Caribbean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The northern coast of Honduras was put under a
tropical storm watch as a late-season, poorly organized tropical
depression with top winds of 35 mph drifted westward across the
Caribbean Sea Saturday.
   The government of Honduras also issued a tropical storm warning
for Swan Island, which has been used as a staging area for supplies
to the Nicaraguan Contras.
   The center of the storm, traveling west at 5 to 10 mph, was about
150 miles southeast of the island after passing well south of
Jamaica late Friday and early Saturday, the National Hurricane
Center reported.
   Little significant change in strength was expected Saturday,
forecasters said. However, conditions were favorable for some
gradual strengthening afterward as it turned to the northwest.
   ``It looks like it's better organized,'' said hurricane
forecaster Hal Gerrish. ``The environment is a little more
favorable'' for development.
   Heavy rains were possible along the path of the depression,
extending several hundred miles to the north and east of the poorly
defined center. Kingston, Jamaica reported nearly 4 inches of rain
over a 24-hour period.
   Small craft along the northern coast of Honduras and Swan Island
were advised to remain in port.
   Atlantic hurricane seasons begin June 1 and end on Nov. 30, with
storm activity usually peaking in mid-September.
</TEXT>
