<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BrokerageRaid     11-19 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brokerage Raid,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Agents Raid Offices of Broker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COLLEEN BARRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Treasury Department and Internal Revenue
Service agents raided the offices of penny-stock broker Blinder,
Robinson & Co. on Saturday, told employees to leave and began going
through records.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission launched an investigation
of the company last year, alleging that customers had been defrauded.
   Alan Jacobson, an attorney for the company, confirmed that a
search warrant had been served covering 53 customers and 15
companies.
   ``They were apparently the subject of an IRS and U.S. Attorney's
Office investigation,'' Jacobson said. ``None of the 53 persons are
presently or formerly associated with or employed under Blinder,
Robinson. None of the companies are underwritten by Blinder,
Robinson. No one told us today that Blinder, Robinson is a target of
the investigation, just that there is an investigation,'' Jacobson
said.
   The agents refused to say what they were looking for.
   The firm recently was the subject of a story on the CBS News
program ``60 Minutes.''
   The commission at the time said it was examining allegations
dating to August 1983 that Blinder, Robinson violated federal law by
marketing nine distributions of unregistered securities by falsely
representing the business prospects of the companies involved, and
by excessively marking up the prices of the securities.
   The SEC also had two other actions pending against the company,
which was the nation's largest penny-stock broker with 66 offices in
37 states.
   Penny stocks are relatively inexpensive and high-risk securities
issued by firms whose shares do not trade on the major stock
exchanges.
   The SEC allegations accused the company of bookkeeping violations.
   The National Association of Securities Dealers also levied
penalties totaling $250,000 against the company in 1987 for charging
excessive markups in the price of shares for one of its issues.
   The shares involved Telephone Exchange Corp. The NASD studied
more than a thousand transactions after Telephone Express went
public in 1984 and found that the company controlled 97 percent of
the transactions and charged excessive prices in all but three
transactions.
   The NASD said markups went as high as 150 percent. NASD rules
limited markups at the time to 10 percent above a brokerage firm's
cost.
   The company was suspended from doing business for five days, and
six executives were suspended from the brokerage business for 90
days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
