<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DoomsdayClock     11-19 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Doomsday Clock,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Scientist Agrees to Help Set `Doomsday Clock' for U.S.
Magazine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet physicist Andrei Sakharov has agreed to
help set the ``Doomsday Clock'' used by the Bulletin of Atomic
Scientists to depict the state of tension among nuclear powers, the
magazine announced Saturday.
   Sakharov, who has been traveling in this country, was contacted
in Cambridge, Mass., by Bernard Feld, a physicist at Massachusetts
Institute of Technology and former editor of the Bulletin.
   ``He was very pleased to be asked and had been interested in the
Bulletin for some time,'' Feld reported to the magazine staff.
   Sakharov becomes the 18th Nobel laureate among the 44 members of
the Bulletin's board of sponsors, which helps decide where to put
the minute hand of the ``Doomsday Clock'' that has been featured on
the cover of the magazine for 41 years.
   At present, it is at six minutes to midnight, one minute closer
to doomsday that it was when it first appeared in 1947. Over the
years, the time has been as distant as 12 minutes and as near as two
minutes.
   By joining the board of sponsors, Sakharov, who won the Nobel
Peace Prize in 1975, ``affirmed a belief in what the Bulletin stands
for,'' said spokeswoman Lisa Grayson.
   She said the magazine's philosphy is that only by informing the
public on the hazards of the nuclear age can a nuclear disaster be
avoided.
</TEXT>
