<1ST_LINE>a a BC-Week'sBusiness Adv19-20-1stAdd   11-19 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Week's Business, Adv 19-20-1st Add,0610</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Nov. 19-20</NOTE>
<HEAD>Repeating for all needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: ... foreign investor.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In other business news this past week:
   _OPEC oil ministers met in Vienna, Austria, to try to fashion a
new production agreement that would limit output and push up prices.
Analysts were skeptical about the chances for success.
   _The government said the trade deficit narrowed by 17 percent to
$10.5 billion in September, but the report wasn't good enough to
rally support for the sagging dollar. Central banks from around the
world bought dollars in the foreign exchange market at week's end in
a coordinated effort to prop up the currency, whose value was
depressed by market worries about the trade and budget deficits.
   _Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told a federal
commission that the budget deficit required urgent action.
President-elect George Bush, seeking to calm the financial markets,
said he intends to tackle the problem quickly in the new
administration.
   _A government report showed retail sales shot up 0.9 percent in
October, the strongest increase in seven months. In other reports,
factory production rose 0.4 percent in October, housing construction
increased 7.2 percent during the month and business inventories were
up 0.7 percent in September.
   _The Big Three automakers said their car sales rose 17.8 percent
in early November over depressed levels in the same period last year.
   _Continental Airlines announced a restructured ``MaxSaver''
program boosting most of its remaining cut-rate fares. Some
competitors followed suit.
   _A special directors committee of RJR Nabisco Inc. was expected
to review competing buyout bids from a management team and another
group led by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. over the weekend. Another
buyout firm, Forstmann Little & Co. and its partners, withdrew from
the bidding. Meanwhile, Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. sued RJR
Nabisco, charging that the takeover planned by Nabisco's management
had devastated the insurer's holdings in Nabisco bonds.
   _Holly Farms Corp. moved to sidestep a hostile takeover by rival
poultry producer Tyson Foods Inc. by agreeing to be acquired by
ConAgra Inc. in a stock swap valued at about $1 billion.
   _MAI Basic Four Inc., a California computer company controlled by
New York investor Bennett S. LeBow, launched an unsolicited $970
million takeover offer for the much larger Prime Computer Inc.
   _A Treasury Department task force studying the savings and loan
crisis concluded that taxpayer money must be spent to rescue the
ailing system.
   _The Supreme Court agreed to hear arguments on whether investor
claims against brokers must be settled by binding arbitration.
   _A federal appeals court refused to oust U.S. District Judge
Milton Pollack from presiding over the civil insider trading case
against Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   _The U.S. Tax Court ruled that points paid in connection with the
refinancing of a home mortgage must be written off over the life of
the loan, rather than in the year the cost was incurred.
   _The Transportation Department ordered a wide range of drug
testing, including random checks, for more than 4 million
transportation workers from airline pilots and flight attendants to
truckers and railroaders.
   _Allstate Insurance Co. said it would stop doing business in
Massachusetts due to losses from the state's tough insurance laws,
echoing anger among insurers nationwide over changing regulatory
climates.
   _Media magnate Rupert Murdoch and nine hotel chains formed a
venture to develop and run a new computerized hotel reservations
system called UltraSwitch. Murdoch also announced plans to begin a
new women's magazine led by Grace Mirabella, who left Vogue in July.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Nov. 19-20</NOTE>
